vil''\n* [[Vandenberg (band)|Vandenberg]] \u2013 ''[[Heading for a Storm]]''\n* [[Vardis]] \u2013 ''The Lion's Share'' (comp)\n* Victim \u2013 ''Power Hungry'' \n* [[Virgin Steele]] \u2013 ''[[Guardians of the Flame (album)|Guardians of the Flame]]''\n* Virgin Steele \u2013 ''[[Wait for the Night]]'' (EP)\n* [[Hawaii (band)|Vixen]] \u2013 ''Made in Hawaii'' (EP)\n* [[Warlord (band)|Warlord]] \u2013 ''Deliver Us'' (EP)\n* [[Warriors (band)|Warriors]] \u2013 ''[[Warriors (1983 Warriors album)|Warriors]]''\n* [[Wild Dogs]] \u2013 ''Wild Dogs''\n* Wildfire \u2013 ''Brute Force and Ignorance''\n* Winterkat \u2013 ''Winterkat'' (EP)\n* [[Witchfinder General (band)|Witchfinder General]] \u2013 ''[[Friends of Hell]]''\n* [[Witchfynde]] \u2013 ''Cloak and Dagger''\n* [[Mark Slaughter|Xcursion]] \u2013 ''Xcursion'' (EP)\n* [[Y&T]] \u2013 ''[[Mean Streak (album)|Mean Streak]]''\n* [[Zebra (American band)|Zebra]] \u2013 ''[[Zebra (Zebra album)|Zebra]]''\n* Zero Nine \u2013 ''Headline''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Events==\n* [[Yngwie Malmsteen]] starts performing in the band [[Steeler (American band)|Steeler]]. Also in that band was vocalist [[Ron Keel]] (later on [[Keel (band)|Keel]]) and former [[W.A.S.P. (band)|W.A.S.P.]] bassist Rik Fox. The band produced only one album, ''[[Steeler (American album)|Steeler]]''.\n* [[Dave Mustaine]], lead guitarist for [[Metallica]], is fired for drug/alcohol abuse, and is replaced by [[Exodus (band)|Exodus]] guitarist [[Kirk Hammett]], after which he forms the L.A. [[thrash metal]] band [[Megadeth]].\n* [[Kiss (band)|KISS]] ended the use of makeup in their act.\n* November 19: the single by [[Quiet Riot]] \"[[Cum on Feel the Noize]]\" is No. 5 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.\n* April 17: [[Mountain (band)|Mountain]] bassist, and [[Cream (band)|Cream]] producer, [[Felix Pappalardi]] was shot and killed by his wife [[Gail Collins Pappalardi]].\n* [[Metallica]] and [[Slayer]] both release their debut albums ''[[Kill 'Em All]]'' and ''[[Show No Mercy (Slayer album)|Show No Mercy]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Timeline box|title=[[Timeline of heavy metal music|Heavy Metal Timeline]]|before=[[1982 in heavy metal music|1982]]|after=[[1984 in heavy metal music|1984]]|year='''1983'''}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Timeline of heavy metal and hard rock music}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1983 In Heavy Metal Music}}\n[[Category:1980s in heavy metal music]]\n[[Category:1983 in music|Metal]]\n", "name_user": "Metalmaniac87", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNewly formed bands", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1983_in_heavy_metal_music"}
{"title_page": "Hemlock Grove (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 American horror thriller television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Hemlock Grove\n| image                = Hemlock Grove Titlecard.jpg\n| genre                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Horror fiction|Horror]]\n* [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]\n}}\n| creator              = Brian McGreevy\n| based_on             = {{based on|''[[Hemlock Grove]]''|Brian McGreevy}}\n| developer            = {{Plainlist|\n* Brian McGreevy\n* Lee Shipman\n}}\n| writer               = {{Plainlist|\n* Brian McGreevy\n* Lee Shipman\n}}\n| director             =  \n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Famke Janssen]]\n* [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]]\n* [[Landon Liboiron]]\n* [[Penelope Mitchell]]\n* [[Kandyse McClure]]\n* [[Freya Tingley]]\n* [[Dougray Scott]]\n* [[Kaniehtiio Horn|Tiio Horn]]\n* [[Joel de la Fuente]]\n* [[Madeleine Martin]]\n* [[Madeline Brewer]]\n* [[Camille De Pazzis]]\n* [[Richard Gunn (actor)|Richard Gunn]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = \n| composer             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Nathan Barr]]\n* Todd Haberman\n}}\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 3\n| num_episodes         = 33\n| list_episodes        = List of Hemlock Grove episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Eli Roth]]\n* [[Charles H. Eglee]]\n* [[Eric Newman (producer)|Eric Newman]]\n* Michael A. Connolly\n* Lee Shipman\n* Brian McGreevy\n* [[Deran Sarafian]]\n* [[Mark Verheiden]]\n* Peter Friedlander\n}}\n| producer             = \n| editor               = \n| location             = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| cinematography       = \n| camera               = \n| runtime              = 45\u201358 minutes\n| company              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gaumont International Television]]\n* ShineBox SMC\n* United Bongo Drum, Inc.\n}}\n| distributor          = [[Netflix]]\n| channel              = Netflix\n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| audio_format         = [[Dolby Digital|Dolby Digital 5.1]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2013|04|19}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2015|10|23}}\n| related              = \n| website              = https://www.netflix.com/title/70242310\n}}\n'''''Hemlock Grove''''' is an American [[Horror fiction|horror]] [[web television]] series produced by [[Eli Roth]] and developed by Brian McGreevy and Lee Shipman. It is a production of [[Gaumont International Television]]. The series is based on McGreevy's 2012 [[Hemlock Grove|novel of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/166843-event-coverage-eli-roth-a-brian-mcgreevy-talk-hemlock-grove|title=Event Coverage: Eli Roth & Brian McGreevy Talk Hemlock Grove|website=ComingSoon.net|date=April 16, 2012|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> The series premiered on [[Netflix]] on April 19, 2013, with all 13 episodes made immediately available for online viewing.<ref name=pressrel>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2013/01/09/hemlock-grove-eli-roths-gothic-thriller-developed-by-brian-mcgreevy-and-lee-shipman-available-only-on-netflix-april-19-626311/20130109netflix01/ |title=\"Hemlock Grove\" Eli Roth's Gothic Thriller Developed by Brian McGreevy & Lee Shipman Available Only on Netflix April 19|date=January 9, 2013|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe show examines the strange happenings in Hemlock Grove, a fictional town in [[Pennsylvania]]. Roman Godfrey, heir to the town's wealthy Godfrey family, befriends the town's newcomer, Peter Rumancek. Recent brutal murders in the town have stirred up rumors, and the two work together to shed light on the case while also hiding their own dark secrets. oooOooH tHe mAcHiNe oF a dream such a cLeaN maChiNe\n\nOn June 19, 2013, Netflix renewed ''Hemlock Grove'' for a second season of 10 episodes, to air in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Seat42f|title=Hemlock Grove Renewed|url=http://www.seat42f.com/hemlock-grove-renewed.html|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> On July 18, 2013, Netflix earned the first [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations for original online-only web television at the [[65th Primetime Emmy Awards]] in 2013. Three of its [[List of original programs distributed by Netflix|online original series]]\u2014''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'', ''Hemlock Grove'', and ''[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]''\u2014earned nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/07/18/watching-for-the-2013-primetime-emmy-nominations/|title=Netflix Does Well in 2013 Primetime Emmy Nominations|accessdate=2013-07-18|date=2013-07-18|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Stelter, Brian}}</ref>\n\nThe second season premiered on July 11, 2014.<ref name=\"Spangler\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/news/netflix-sets-premiere-date-for-eli-roths-hemlock-grove-season-2-1201156772/ |title=Netflix Sets Premiere Date for Eli Roth\u2019s \u2018Hemlock Grove\u2019 Season 2|date=April 14, 2014|last=Spangler|first=Todd|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=April 14, 2014}}</ref> On September 2, 2014, Netflix renewed it for a third and final 10-episode season,<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie|title=Netflix Renews 'Hemlock Grove' for Third and Final Season |url=https://deadline.com/2014/09/hemlock-grove-renewed-third-final-season-netflix-827896/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=2 September 2014|date=2 September 2014}}</ref> which premiered on October 23, 2015.<ref name=\"season 3\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/08/hemlock-grove-season-3-teaser-premiere-date-netflix-1201508147/|title=\u2018Hemlock Grove\u2019 Final-Season Teaser & Premiere Date: Bloodlust Redefined|first=Erik|last=Pedersen|date=August 27, 2015|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"season 3 confirmation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whats-on-netflix.com/whats-new/new-titles-on-netflix-us-oct-23-2015/|title=New Titles on Netflix US (Oct, 23)|date=October 23, 2014|last=Pease|first=Jasmin|access-date=October 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202212029/http://www.whats-on-netflix.com/whats-new/new-titles-on-netflix-us-oct-23-2015/|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{further|List of Hemlock Grove episodes}}\nThe series is set in the town of Hemlock Grove, Pennsylvania. The town is a mixture of extreme wealth and poverty, as the closing of the town's steel mill many years earlier caused many to lose their jobs. The town's main sources of employment are now the Godfrey Institute for Biomedical Technologies and Hemlock Acres Hospital. Heading the Institute\u2014which is rumored to conduct sinister experiments on a daily basis\u2014is the imposing Olivia Godfrey ([[Famke Janssen]]), while Hemlock Acres' lead psychiatrist is Olivia's dead husband's brother, Dr. Norman Godfrey ([[Dougray Scott]]).\n\nAs season one opens, the town's rumor mill turns even more twisted, as two teenage girls are brutally killed and their bodies left for unsuspecting people to find the next day. Peter Rumancek ([[Landon Liboiron]]) a 17-year-old [[Romani people|Romani]] boy, is suspected of the crimes by some of the townsfolk; he is also rumored to be a [[werewolf]]. Secretly, he is, in fact, a werewolf, and, along with the heir to the Godfrey estate, the troubled Roman Godfrey ([[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]]), he sets out to solve the mystery.\n\nRounding out the main cast of characters of the first season are Norman's daughter (Roman's cousin), the beautiful, Letha Godfrey ([[Penelope Mitchell]]) who claims the father of her unborn child is an angel from Heaven, and Christina Wendall ([[Freya Tingley]]), a lonely girl who becomes interested in Peter.\n\nFor season two, two former supporting characters were promoted to the main cast of characters: Peter's [[con-artist]] older cousin Destiny ([[Tiio Horn]]), who makes her living as a [[psychic medium]], and Dr. Johann Pryce ([[Joel de la Fuente]]), the lead scientist of the Godfrey Institute, a [[mad scientist|brilliant but ruthless man of science]], gifted with [[super-strength]]. A cult has arisen that is bent on destroying the supernatural creatures in Hemlock Grove by any means necessary. To make matters worse, both Peter and Roman struggle with their nature, as Peter risks becoming the same killer from the first season and Roman, after his full immersion with his true nature in the first season, has developed an insatiable hunger to kill. As they fight their enemies and deal with their situations, they must also deal with the monsters they are becoming, or have already become.\n{{:List of Hemlock Grove episodes}}\n\n== Cast ==\n\n=== Main ===\n* [[Famke Janssen]] as Olivia Godfrey\n* [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] as Roman Godfrey\n* [[Landon Liboiron]] as Peter Rumancek \n* [[Penelope Mitchell]] as Letha Godfrey (season 1)\n* [[Freya Tingley]] as Christina Wendall (season 1)\n* [[Kaniehtiio Horn]] as Destiny Rumancek (season 2\u20133; recurring season 1)\n* [[Joel de la Fuente]] as Dr. Johann Pryce (season 2\u20133; recurring season 1)\n* [[Dougray Scott]] as Dr. Norman Godfrey (season 1\u20132)\n* Nicole Boivin (recurring season 1) and [[Madeleine Martin]] (season 3; recurring season 2),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/10/victoria-justice-in-eye-candy-madeleine-martin-boards-hemlock-grove-troy-garrity-in-hbo-pilot-ballers/#|title=Victoria Justice In \u2018Eye Candy\u2019, Madeleine Martin Boards \u2018Hemlock Grove\u2019, Troy Garity In HBO Pilot \u2018Ballers\u2019|first=The Deadline|last=Team|date=October 11, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> as Shelley Godfrey, Roman's heavily deformed but good-hearted sister. While Boivin and Martin are the main actresses portraying the character, Shelley's remarkably large figure is provided, when seen from a distance, by [[Amazon Eve]] for the first five episodes, and by Michael Andreae thereafter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://serenitywomble.wordpress.com/2013/04/22/review-hemlock-grove-season-one/|title=Review: Hemlock Grove, Season One|first=Serenity|last=Womble|date=April 22, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Camille De Pazzis]] as Annie Archambeau (season 3)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/camille-de-pazzis-cast-hemlock-grove-zara-zoe-tnt-pilot-lumen-1201318992/ |title=Camille de Pazzis Joins 'Hemlock Grove'; Zara Zoe In TNT Pilot 'Lumen' |author=The Deadline Team|date=December 11, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Recurring ===\n* [[Lili Taylor]] as Lynda Rumancek, Peter's mother and confidant (season 1\u20132)\n* [[Laurie Fortier]] as Marie Godfrey, Norman's wife, and the mother of Letha (season 1\u20132)\n* [[Kandyse McClure]] as Dr. Clementine Chasseur, a mysterious woman arriving in Hemlock Grove to investigate the killings (season 1)\n* [[Aaron Douglas (actor)|Aaron Douglas]] as Tom Sworn, the sheriff of Hemlock Grove (season 1)\n* Ted Dykstra as Francis Pullman, the \"[[village idiot]]\", who claims to have witnessed unspeakable things (season 1)\n* [[Demore Barnes]] as Michael Chasseur, Clementine's brother\n* Luke Camilleri as Andreas Vasilescu (season 2\u20133) \n* [[JC MacKenzie]] as Dr. Arnold Spivak (season 2\u20133)\n* [[Madeline Brewer]] as Miranda Cates (season 2\u20133)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/10/michael-malarkey-joins-the-vampire-diaries-madeline-brewer-in-hemlock-grove/|title=Michael Malarkey Joins \u2018The Vampire Diaries\u2019, Madeline Brewer In \u2018Hemlock Grove\u2019|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=October 9, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://instagram.com/p/fQe9MFHoh4/|title=Madeline Brewer's instagram|publisher=|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Shauna MacDonald]] as Dr. Galina Zheleznova-Burdukovskaya (formerly Alyona Potyomkina-Zosimova), a brilliant Russian scientist working under Dr. Pryce (season 2)\n* [[Alex Hernandez (actor)|Alex Hernandez]] as Isaac Ochoa, a private detective (season 3)\n* [[Richard Gunn (actor)|Richard Gunn]] as Aitor Quantic (season 3)\n* [[Michael Therriault]] as Dr. Klaus Blinsky (season 3)\n* [[Anthony J. Mifsud]] as Greek Delivery man (season 3)\n* Meegwun Fairbrother as Milan Faber (season 3)\n\n=== Guest ===\n* [[Eliana Jones]] and [[Emilia McCarthy]] as Alexa and Alyssa Sworn, Sheriff Sworn's twin daughters, and Christina's best friends\n* [[Holly Deveaux]] as Jenny Fredericks, a local convenience store clerk\n* [[Don Francks]] as Nicolae Rumancek, Peter's deceased grandfather. Seen in flashbacks.\n* [[Philip Craig (actor)|Philip Craig]] as the Bishop, a contact of Clementine's\n* Alanis Peart as Mrs. Pisarro, Peter's and Roman's English teacher\n* Emily Piggford as Ashley Valentine, a schoolmate of Roman's who develops a crush on him\n* Jacqueline Graham as Lisa Willoughby, a local girl who becomes the second murder victim\n* [[Paul Popowich]] as JR Godfrey, Roman's deceased father, husband of Olivia, and brother of Norman. Seen in flashbacks.\n* Landon Norris as Tyler, a fellow schoolmate, with a romantic interest in Christina\n* Joe Bostick as Vice Principal Spears, the vice principal of the local high school\n* [[Lorenza Izzo]] as Brooke Bluebell, a local girl, whose brutal murder opens the series\n* [[Marty Adams]],  [[William deVry]], [[Jasmin Geljo]], [[Ashleigh Harrington]] and Dylan Trowbridge portray the town's Deputy Sheriffs, nicknamed respectively Neck, Chin, Moustache, Lips, and Nose\n\n==Development and production==\n\nIn December 2011, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that Netflix and Gaumont International Television were finalizing a deal for a 13-episode series order for ''Hemlock Grove''.<ref name=neardeal>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/12/netflix-nears-13-episode-order-for-horror-drama-hemlock-grove-from-eli-roth-and-gaumont-international-television/|title=Netflix Nears Order For Eli Roth Horror Drama 'Hemlock Grove' From Eli Roth And Gaumont International Television|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=December 12, 2011|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508110413/http://www.deadline.com/2011/12/netflix-nears-13-episode-order-for-horror-drama-hemlock-grove-from-eli-roth-and-gaumont-international-television/|archive-date=May 8, 2012}}</ref> The project was officially announced in March 2012.<ref name=03-21-12>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2012/03/21/only-on-netflix-premier-horror-suspense-director-eli-roth-reanimates-the-gothic-novel-with-hemlock-grove-981305/20120321netflix01/|title=Only on Netflix: Premier Horror Suspense Director Eli Roth Reanimates the Gothic Novel With \"Hemlock Grove\"|date=March 21, 2012|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref> Eli Roth serves as an executive producer and will direct the pilot, ''Jellyfish In the Sky''.<ref name=neardeal/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/173201-wondercon-interview-eli-roth-on-hemlock-grove-werewolf-transformation|title=Horror Movies: Reviews, Trailers, News - Shock Till You Drop|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> [[Deran Sarafian]], who signed on in mid-March as an executive producer/series director, directed six episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/hemlock-grove-panel-recap-wondercon/|title=WonderCon 2013: HEMLOCK GROVE Panel Recap Featuring Eli Roth and Famke Janssen|date=March 29, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/03/deran-sarafian-signs-with-wme-joins-hemlock-grove-as-executive-producer/|title=Deran Sarafian Signs With WME, Joins 'Hemlock Grove' As Executive Producer|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=March 16, 2012|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317204545/http://www.deadline.com/2012/03/deran-sarafian-signs-with-wme-joins-hemlock-grove-as-executive-producer/|archive-date=March 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter McGreevy pushed for the series to be filmed in the Pittsburgh area, production was expected to start in early June 2012 and last until November.<ref name=morehemlock>{{cite web|url=http://communityvoices.sites.post-gazette.com/index.php/arts-entertainment-living/tuned-in-journal/32407-more-on-hemlock-grove-the-tv-series|title=More on 'Hemlock Grove,' the TV series|last=Owen|first=Rob|date=March 28, 2012|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|accessdate=July 3, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501032627/http://communityvoices.sites.post-gazette.com/index.php/arts-entertainment-living/tuned-in-journal/32407-more-on-hemlock-grove-the-tv-series|archive-date=May 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=wantedPA>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/tv-radio/author-brian-mcgreevy-pulled-to-have-tv-series-filmed-near-pittsburgh-628400/|title=Author Brian McGreevy pulled to have 'Hemlock Grove' series filmed near Pittsburgh|last=Owen|first=Rob|date=May 9, 2012|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref> In mid May, Gaumont International Television pulled out of Pennsylvania in favor of production at the [[Cinespace Film Studios]] in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://playbackonline.ca/2012/06/04/hemlock-grove-shoot-books-torontos-cinespace-stage|title=Hemlock Grove shoot books Toronto\u2019s Cinespace stage|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|date=June 4, 2012|work=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]]|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> The move came about after Gaumont management had a misunderstanding on how the [[Pennsylvania Film Production Tax Credit|Pennsylvania Film Tax Credit]] program works.<ref name=pullplug>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/tv-radio/tv-series-pulls-plug-on-filming-here-635575/?p=0|title=TV series pulls plug on filming here|date=May 12, 2012|last=Owen|first=Rob|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref> Filming began on July 13, 2012 in [[Port Perry]], [[Ontario]]; a small town about 40 miles (63&nbsp;km) northeast of Toronto that has been transformed to look like Hemlock Grove, the fictional Western Pennsylvania town the series is set in.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1392348--film-crews-to-return-to-port-perry|title=Film crews to return to Port Perry|last=Hall|first=Chris|date=March 16, 2012|work=durhamregion.com|accessdate=July 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401134440/http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1392348--film-crews-to-return-to-port-perry|archive-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe budget for the first season of ''Hemlock Grove'' is reportedly about $45 million.<ref name=pullplug/>\n\nFilming took place in Toronto at St Clair and Yonge at the [[Deer Park United Church]] and in [[Hamilton, Ontario]] at [[Hamilton Cemetery]].  Hemlock Grove High School was filmed at [[Ursula Franklin Academy]]/ [[Western Technical Commercial School]] in Toronto.  It was also filmed in [[Oshawa]] at the [[Parkwood Estate]]; the opening scene of Season 1, Episode 1 is on Queen Street in Port Perry, Ontario.\n\n===Casting===\nIn March, Netflix announced that [[Famke Janssen]] and [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] would star in the series, Janssen as Olivia Godfrey and Skarsg\u00e5rd as her son, Roman Godfrey.<ref name=03-21-12/> In early April 2012, it was revealed that Peter Rumancek would be portrayed by [[Landon Liboiron]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/terra-nova-landon-liboiron-netflix-hemlock-grove-eli-roth-307348 |title=Terra Nova's' Landon Liboiron Joins Netflix's 'Hemlock Grove' (Exclusive)|date=April 3, 2012|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> On April 4, Penelope Mitchell was cast as Roman's cousin, Letha Godfrey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/04/series-hemlock-grove-pilots-malibu-country-louis-ckferesten-add-to-casts/|title=Series 'Hemlock Grove', Pilots 'Malibu Country' & Louis CK/Feresten Add To Casts|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=April 2, 2012|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622174605/http://www.deadline.com/2012/04/series-hemlock-grove-pilots-malibu-country-louis-ckferesten-add-to-casts/|archive-date=June 22, 2012}}</ref> Freya Tingley was cast as Christina Wendall on April 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/04/latarsha-rose-cast-in-bets-mary-jane-freya-tingley-in-netflixs-hemlock-grove/|title=Latarsha Rose, Omari Hardwick Join 'Mary Jane'; Freya Tingley To 'Hemlock Grove'|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=April 10, 2012|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622174352/http://www.deadline.com/2012/04/latarsha-rose-cast-in-bets-mary-jane-freya-tingley-in-netflixs-hemlock-grove/|archive-date=June 22, 2012}}</ref> On April 12, [[Dougray Scott]] was announced as Dr. Norman Godfrey, Olivia's brother-in-law and Letha's father.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/04/dougray-scott-to-star-in-netflixs-hemlock-grove/|title=Dougray Scott To Star In Netflix's 'Hemlock Grove'|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=April 12, 2012|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623090441/http://www.deadline.com/2012/04/dougray-scott-to-star-in-netflixs-hemlock-grove/|archive-date=June 23, 2012}}</ref> On July 2, [[Lili Taylor]] was cast as Peter Rumancek's mother, and [[Kandyse McClure]] was cast as Dr. Chasseur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2012/07/02/lili-taylor-hemlock-grove/|title=Exclusive: Six Feet Under Vet Lili Taylor Joins Netflix Thriller Series Hemlock Grove|last=Roots|first=Kimberly|date=July 2, 2012|work=[[TVLine]]|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120704215157/http://tvline.com/2012/07/02/lili-taylor-hemlock-grove/|archive-date=July 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/07/kandyse-mcclure-joins-cast-of-hemlock-grove/|title=Kandyse McClure Joins Cast Of 'Hemlock Grove'|date=July 2, 2012|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120705230949/http://www.deadline.com/2012/07/kandyse-mcclure-joins-cast-of-hemlock-grove/|archive-date=July 5, 2012}}</ref> [[Aaron Douglas (actor)|Aaron Douglas]] was cast as Sheriff Sworn on July 8.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/07/netflix-castings-house-of-cards-hemlock-grove/|title=Netflix Castings: 'House Of Cards', 'Hemlock Grove'|first=The Deadline|last=Team|date=July 8, 2012|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> In late July 2012, [[Kaniehtiio Horn]] joined the cast as Destiny Rumancek.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/hemlock-grove-netflix-tiio-horn-355974 |title='18 to Life' Alum to Play Gypsy Witch-Prostitute on Netflix's 'Hemlock Grove' (Exclusive)|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|date=March 16, 2012|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=July 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe music for seasons 1 and 2 was composed by [[Nathan Barr]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2012/05/29/nathan-barr-to-score-eli-roths-hemlock-grove/|title=Nathan Barr to Score Eli Roth's 'Hemlock Grove'|date=July 8, 2012|work=filmmusicreporter.com|accessdate=July 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603175518/http://filmmusicreporter.com/2012/05/29/nathan-barr-to-score-eli-roths-hemlock-grove/|archive-date=June 3, 2012}}</ref> In October 2015, it was announced that Todd Haberman would join Barr to score season 3.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Todd Haberman Co-Scoring 'Hemlock Grove' Season 3 {{!}} Film Music Reporter|url = http://filmmusicreporter.com/2015/10/20/todd-haberman-co-scoring-hemlock-grove-season-3/|accessdate = 2015-10-20}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Viewership===\nAfter its opening weekend, Netflix announced that \"''Hemlock Grove'' was viewed by more members globally in its first weekend than  ''[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2013/04/22/netflix-hemlock-grove-first-weekend/|title=Netflix says more members watched \u2018Hemlock Grove\u2019 on first weekend than \u2018House of Cards\u2019|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe first season of ''Hemlock Grove'' received \"mixed or average\" reviews, according to [[Metacritic]], with a score of 45 out of 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/hemlock-grove/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for Hemlock Grove Season 1 |publisher=Metacritic |date= |accessdate=2013-07-02}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the season has a rating of 26%, based on 34 reviews, and the average rating is 4.68/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Hemlock Grove'' is an ugly, unpleasant affair that throws crazy ideas together without much forethought.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/hemlock_grove/s01|title=Hemlock Grove: Season 1 - Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe second season received \"generally unfavorable\" reviews, according to Metacritic, with a score of 37 out of 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/hemlock-grove/season-2|title=Hemlock Grove|publisher=|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref> Rotten Tomatoes gives the season a rating of 55%, based on 11 reviews, and the average rating is 5.29/10. The site's consensus reads: \"''Hemlock Grove'' jettisons some of its most grating qualities while doubling down on its splashy gore, making for a more engaging second season \u2013 but the series frustratingly remains a shoddy amalgamation of gothic tropes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/hemlock_grove/s02|title=Hemlock Grove: Season 2 - Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMary McNamara of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called ''Hemlock Grove'' \"terrible\",<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-hemlock-grove-review-netflix-20130419,0,2823333.story | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | last=McNamara | first=Mary | accessdate=April 22, 2013 | date = April 19, 2013 | title=TV review: 'Hemlock Grove' wallows in its own fake guts}}</ref> and Alison Willmore of [[IndieWire]], \"a mess\".<ref>{{cite web | date=April 19, 2013 | accessdate=April 22, 2013 | last=Willmore | first=Alison | url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/hemlock-grove-review-netflix | title=Netflix's New Series 'Hemlock Grove' is a Ramshackle, Sometimes Interesting Mess of Supernatural Themes and Teen Angst | work=[[IndieWire]]}}</ref> Zack Handlen of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave the series an F, calling it \"a shockingly inane misstep, a ponderous mess.\"<ref name=avclub>{{cite web|last=Handlen|first=Zack|title='Hemlock Grove' {{!}} Other Shows {{!}} TV Club|url=https://www.avclub.com/articles/hemlock-grove,96734/|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=April 21, 2013|date=April 20, 2013}}</ref> Dante D'Orazio of ''[[The Verge]]'' said the show was \"universally panned\" on account of its \"poor acting, slow plot development, and ... style that's off-key.\"<ref>{{cite web | last=D'Orazio | first=Dante | work=[[The Verge]] | url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/4/19/4242486/netflix-hemlock-grove-television-series-arrives-today | title=Netflix's 'Hemlock Grove' arrives amidst storm of negative reviews | date=April 19, 2013 | accessdate=April 22, 2013}}</ref>  Patrick Smith of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' said that ''Hemlock Grove'' was \"corny and emphatically less profound than it thinks it is\", giving it two out of five stars overall.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Patrick|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10004169/Hemlock-Grove-Netflix-review.html|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |title=Hemlock Grove, Netflix, review}}</ref> James Poniewozik of ''Time'' listed the series as one of the worst ten things on television in 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/12/17/here-are-10-of-the-worst-things-tv-did-this-year/ | title=Here Are 10 of the Worst Things TV Did This Year | last=Poniewozik | first=James | publisher=Time | date=2013-12-17 | accessdate = 2014-01-01 }}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, David Hiltbrand of the ''Philadelphia Inquirer'' said that the show \"manages to be lush, gross, frightening, and ridiculous--all at the same time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/2013-04-19/news/38649954_1_hemlock-grove-leto-netflix|title=Archives - Philly.com|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> Tom Gliatto of ''People Weekly'' reviewed the series positively, with a score of 75 out of 100: \"The acting is good, especially Bill Skarsgard and Landon Liboiron.... I like the show's languid, dreamlike beauty, but horror fans may be less patient.\" Jessica Shaw of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the series a B+.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2013/04/19/hemlock-grove-netflix-review/|title='Hemlock Grove' review: Gory Netflix series has beating heart|date=April 19, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n''Hemlock Grove'' received two nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music|Outstanding Main Title Theme Music]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Visual Effects]] at the [[65th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/hemlock-grove|title=Hemlock Grove|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2013\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[65th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music|Outstanding Original Main Title Theme Music]]\n|[[Nathan Barr]]\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/sites/default/files/2013CreativeArtsEmmysWinners.pdf|title=Creative Arts Emmy Awards Winners|publisher=emmys.com|date=|accessdate=2013-09-15}}</ref> \n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Visual Effects|Outstanding Special Visual Effects]]\n| Episode:\"Children of the Night\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|2014\n|[[Visual Effects Society Awards 2014|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n|Outstanding Visual Effects in a Visual Effects-Driven Photoreal/Live Action Broadcast Program\n|Matt Whelan, Chris Brown<br> Todd Masters, Jonathan Banta<br> Eric McAvoy\n|{{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|first=Erik|last=Pedersen|title=VES Awards 2015: Complete Winners List|url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/ves-awards-winners-2015-visual-effects-society-award-winner-list-1201366460/|accessdate=February 4, 2015|newspaper=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Werewolf fiction]]\n*[[List of vampire television series]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Netflix title}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{Netflix original ended series}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American high school television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American horror television series]]\n[[Category:2013 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2015 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American thriller television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fictional representations of Romani people]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Television series by Gaumont International Television]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Hamilton, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Television about werewolves]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013 American horror thriller television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Hemlock Grove\n| image                = Hemlock Grove Titlecard.jpg\n| genre                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Horror fiction|Horror]]\n* [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]\n}}\n| creator              = Brian McGreevy\n| based_on             = {{based on|''[[Hemlock Grove]]''|Brian McGreevy}}\n| developer            = {{Plainlist|\n* Brian McGreevy\n* Lee Shipman\n}}\n| writer               = {{Plainlist|\n* Brian McGreevy\n* Lee Shipman\n}}\n| director             =  \n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Famke Janssen]]\n* [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]]\n* [[Landon Liboiron]]\n* [[Penelope Mitchell]]\n* [[Kandyse McClure]]\n* [[Freya Tingley]]\n* [[Dougray Scott]]\n* [[Kaniehtiio Horn|Tiio Horn]]\n* [[Joel de la Fuente]]\n* [[Madeleine Martin]]\n* [[Madeline Brewer]]\n* [[Camille De Pazzis]]\n* [[Richard Gunn (actor)|Richard Gunn]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = \n| composer             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Nathan Barr]]\n* Todd Haberman\n}}\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 3\n| num_episodes         = 33\n| list_episodes        = List of Hemlock Grove episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Eli Roth]]\n* [[Charles H. Eglee]]\n* [[Eric Newman (producer)|Eric Newman]]\n* Michael A. Connolly\n* Lee Shipman\n* Brian McGreevy\n* [[Deran Sarafian]]\n* [[Mark Verheiden]]\n* Peter Friedlander\n}}\n| producer             = \n| editor               = \n| location             = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| cinematography       = \n| camera               = \n| runtime              = 45\u201358 minutes\n| company              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gaumont International Television]]\n* ShineBox SMC\n* United Bongo Drum, Inc.\n}}\n| distributor          = [[Netflix]]\n| channel              = Netflix\n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| audio_format         = [[Dolby Digital|Dolby Digital 5.1]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2013|04|19}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2015|10|23}}\n| related              = \n| website              = https://www.netflix.com/title/70242310\n}}\n'''''Hemlock Grove''''' is an American [[Horror fiction|horror]] [[web television]] series produced by [[Eli Roth]] and developed by Brian McGreevy and Lee Shipman. It is a production of [[Gaumont International Television]]. The series is based on McGreevy's 2012 [[Hemlock Grove|novel of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/166843-event-coverage-eli-roth-a-brian-mcgreevy-talk-hemlock-grove|title=Event Coverage: Eli Roth & Brian McGreevy Talk Hemlock Grove|website=ComingSoon.net|date=April 16, 2012|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> The series premiered on [[Netflix]] on April 19, 2013, with all 13 episodes made immediately available for online viewing.<ref name=pressrel>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2013/01/09/hemlock-grove-eli-roths-gothic-thriller-developed-by-brian-mcgreevy-and-lee-shipman-available-only-on-netflix-april-19-626311/20130109netflix01/ |title=\"Hemlock Grove\" Eli Roth's Gothic Thriller Developed by Brian McGreevy & Lee Shipman Available Only on Netflix April 19|date=January 9, 2013|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe show examines the strange happenings in Hemlock Grove, a fictional town in [[Pennsylvania]]. Roman Godfrey, heir to the town's wealthy Godfrey family, befriends the town's newcomer, Peter Rumancek. Recent brutal murders in the town have stirred up rumors, and the two work together to shed light on the case while also hiding their own dark secrets.\n\nOn June 19, 2013, Netflix renewed ''Hemlock Grove'' for a second season of 10 episodes, to air in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Seat42f|title=Hemlock Grove Renewed|url=http://www.seat42f.com/hemlock-grove-renewed.html|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> On July 18, 2013, Netflix earned the first [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations for original online-only web television at the [[65th Primetime Emmy Awards]] in 2013. Three of its [[List of original programs distributed by Netflix|online original series]]\u2014''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'', ''Hemlock Grove'', and ''[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]''\u2014earned nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/07/18/watching-for-the-2013-primetime-emmy-nominations/|title=Netflix Does Well in 2013 Primetime Emmy Nominations|accessdate=2013-07-18|date=2013-07-18|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Stelter, Brian}}</ref>\n\nThe second season premiered on July 11, 2014.<ref name=\"Spangler\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/news/netflix-sets-premiere-date-for-eli-roths-hemlock-grove-season-2-1201156772/ |title=Netflix Sets Premiere Date for Eli Roth\u2019s \u2018Hemlock Grove\u2019 Season 2|date=April 14, 2014|last=Spangler|first=Todd|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=April 14, 2014}}</ref> On September 2, 2014, Netflix renewed it for a third and final 10-episode season,<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie|title=Netflix Renews 'Hemlock Grove' for Third and Final Season |url=https://deadline.com/2014/09/hemlock-grove-renewed-third-final-season-netflix-827896/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=2 September 2014|date=2 September 2014}}</ref> which premiered on October 23, 2015.<ref name=\"season 3\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/08/hemlock-grove-season-3-teaser-premiere-date-netflix-1201508147/|title=\u2018Hemlock Grove\u2019 Final-Season Teaser & Premiere Date: Bloodlust Redefined|first=Erik|last=Pedersen|date=August 27, 2015|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"season 3 confirmation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whats-on-netflix.com/whats-new/new-titles-on-netflix-us-oct-23-2015/|title=New Titles on Netflix US (Oct, 23)|date=October 23, 2014|last=Pease|first=Jasmin|access-date=October 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202212029/http://www.whats-on-netflix.com/whats-new/new-titles-on-netflix-us-oct-23-2015/|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{further|List of Hemlock Grove episodes}}\nThe series is set in the town of Hemlock Grove, Pennsylvania. The town is a mixture of extreme wealth and poverty, as the closing of the town's steel mill many years earlier caused many to lose their jobs. The town's main sources of employment are now the Godfrey Institute for Biomedical Technologies and Hemlock Acres Hospital. Heading the Institute\u2014which is rumored to conduct sinister experiments on a daily basis\u2014is the imposing Olivia Godfrey ([[Famke Janssen]]), while Hemlock Acres' lead psychiatrist is Olivia's dead husband's brother, Dr. Norman Godfrey ([[Dougray Scott]]).\n\nAs season one opens, the town's rumor mill turns even more twisted, as two teenage girls are brutally killed and their bodies left for unsuspecting people to find the next day. Peter Rumancek ([[Landon Liboiron]]) a 17-year-old [[Romani people|Romani]] boy, is suspected of the crimes by some of the townsfolk; he is also rumored to be a [[werewolf]]. Secretly, he is, in fact, a werewolf, and, along with the heir to the Godfrey estate, the troubled Roman Godfrey ([[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]]), he sets out to solve the mystery.\n\nRounding out the main cast of characters of the first season are Norman's daughter (Roman's cousin), the beautiful, Letha Godfrey ([[Penelope Mitchell]]) who claims the father of her unborn child is an angel from Heaven, and Christina Wendall ([[Freya Tingley]]), a lonely girl who becomes interested in Peter.\n\nFor season two, two former supporting characters were promoted to the main cast of characters: Peter's [[con-artist]] older cousin Destiny ([[Tiio Horn]]), who makes her living as a [[psychic medium]], and Dr. Johann Pryce ([[Joel de la Fuente]]), the lead scientist of the Godfrey Institute, a [[mad scientist|brilliant but ruthless man of science]], gifted with [[super-strength]]. A cult has arisen that is bent on destroying the supernatural creatures in Hemlock Grove by any means necessary. To make matters worse, both Peter and Roman struggle with their nature, as Peter risks becoming the same killer from the first season and Roman, after his full immersion with his true nature in the first season, has developed an insatiable hunger to kill. As they fight their enemies and deal with their situations, they must also deal with the monsters they are becoming, or have already become.\n{{:List of Hemlock Grove episodes}}\n\n== Cast ==\n\n=== Main ===\n* [[Famke Janssen]] as Olivia Godfrey\n* [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] as Roman Godfrey\n* [[Landon Liboiron]] as Peter Rumancek \n* [[Penelope Mitchell]] as Letha Godfrey (season 1)\n* [[Freya Tingley]] as Christina Wendall (season 1)\n* [[Kaniehtiio Horn]] as Destiny Rumancek (season 2\u20133; recurring season 1)\n* [[Joel de la Fuente]] as Dr. Johann Pryce (season 2\u20133; recurring season 1)\n* [[Dougray Scott]] as Dr. Norman Godfrey (season 1\u20132)\n* Nicole Boivin (recurring season 1) and [[Madeleine Martin]] (season 3; recurring season 2),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/10/victoria-justice-in-eye-candy-madeleine-martin-boards-hemlock-grove-troy-garrity-in-hbo-pilot-ballers/#|title=Victoria Justice In \u2018Eye Candy\u2019, Madeleine Martin Boards \u2018Hemlock Grove\u2019, Troy Garity In HBO Pilot \u2018Ballers\u2019|first=The Deadline|last=Team|date=October 11, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> as Shelley Godfrey, Roman's heavily deformed but good-hearted sister. While Boivin and Martin are the main actresses portraying the character, Shelley's remarkably large figure is provided, when seen from a distance, by [[Amazon Eve]] for the first five episodes, and by Michael Andreae thereafter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://serenitywomble.wordpress.com/2013/04/22/review-hemlock-grove-season-one/|title=Review: Hemlock Grove, Season One|first=Serenity|last=Womble|date=April 22, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Camille De Pazzis]] as Annie Archambeau (season 3)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/camille-de-pazzis-cast-hemlock-grove-zara-zoe-tnt-pilot-lumen-1201318992/ |title=Camille de Pazzis Joins 'Hemlock Grove'; Zara Zoe In TNT Pilot 'Lumen' |author=The Deadline Team|date=December 11, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Recurring ===\n* [[Lili Taylor]] as Lynda Rumancek, Peter's mother and confidant (season 1\u20132)\n* [[Laurie Fortier]] as Marie Godfrey, Norman's wife, and the mother of Letha (season 1\u20132)\n* [[Kandyse McClure]] as Dr. Clementine Chasseur, a mysterious woman arriving in Hemlock Grove to investigate the killings (season 1)\n* [[Aaron Douglas (actor)|Aaron Douglas]] as Tom Sworn, the sheriff of Hemlock Grove (season 1)\n* Ted Dykstra as Francis Pullman, the \"[[village idiot]]\", who claims to have witnessed unspeakable things (season 1)\n* [[Demore Barnes]] as Michael Chasseur, Clementine's brother\n* Luke Camilleri as Andreas Vasilescu (season 2\u20133) \n* [[JC MacKenzie]] as Dr. Arnold Spivak (season 2\u20133)\n* [[Madeline Brewer]] as Miranda Cates (season 2\u20133)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/10/michael-malarkey-joins-the-vampire-diaries-madeline-brewer-in-hemlock-grove/|title=Michael Malarkey Joins \u2018The Vampire Diaries\u2019, Madeline Brewer In \u2018Hemlock Grove\u2019|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=October 9, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://instagram.com/p/fQe9MFHoh4/|title=Madeline Brewer's instagram|publisher=|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Shauna MacDonald]] as Dr. Galina Zheleznova-Burdukovskaya (formerly Alyona Potyomkina-Zosimova), a brilliant Russian scientist working under Dr. Pryce (season 2)\n* [[Alex Hernandez (actor)|Alex Hernandez]] as Isaac Ochoa, a private detective (season 3)\n* [[Richard Gunn (actor)|Richard Gunn]] as Aitor Quantic (season 3)\n* [[Michael Therriault]] as Dr. Klaus Blinsky (season 3)\n* [[Anthony J. Mifsud]] as Greek Delivery man (season 3)\n* Meegwun Fairbrother as Milan Faber (season 3)\n\n=== Guest ===\n* [[Eliana Jones]] and [[Emilia McCarthy]] as Alexa and Alyssa Sworn, Sheriff Sworn's twin daughters, and Christina's best friends\n* [[Holly Deveaux]] as Jenny Fredericks, a local convenience store clerk\n* [[Don Francks]] as Nicolae Rumancek, Peter's deceased grandfather. Seen in flashbacks.\n* [[Philip Craig (actor)|Philip Craig]] as the Bishop, a contact of Clementine's\n* Alanis Peart as Mrs. Pisarro, Peter's and Roman's English teacher\n* Emily Piggford as Ashley Valentine, a schoolmate of Roman's who develops a crush on him\n* Jacqueline Graham as Lisa Willoughby, a local girl who becomes the second murder victim\n* [[Paul Popowich]] as JR Godfrey, Roman's deceased father, husband of Olivia, and brother of Norman. Seen in flashbacks.\n* Landon Norris as Tyler, a fellow schoolmate, with a romantic interest in Christina\n* Joe Bostick as Vice Principal Spears, the vice principal of the local high school\n* [[Lorenza Izzo]] as Brooke Bluebell, a local girl, whose brutal murder opens the series\n* [[Marty Adams]],  [[William deVry]], [[Jasmin Geljo]], [[Ashleigh Harrington]] and Dylan Trowbridge portray the town's Deputy Sheriffs, nicknamed respectively Neck, Chin, Moustache, Lips, and Nose\n\n==Development and production==\n\nIn December 2011, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that Netflix and Gaumont International Television were finalizing a deal for a 13-episode series order for ''Hemlock Grove''.<ref name=neardeal>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/12/netflix-nears-13-episode-order-for-horror-drama-hemlock-grove-from-eli-roth-and-gaumont-international-television/|title=Netflix Nears Order For Eli Roth Horror Drama 'Hemlock Grove' From Eli Roth And Gaumont International Television|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=December 12, 2011|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508110413/http://www.deadline.com/2011/12/netflix-nears-13-episode-order-for-horror-drama-hemlock-grove-from-eli-roth-and-gaumont-international-television/|archive-date=May 8, 2012}}</ref> The project was officially announced in March 2012.<ref name=03-21-12>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2012/03/21/only-on-netflix-premier-horror-suspense-director-eli-roth-reanimates-the-gothic-novel-with-hemlock-grove-981305/20120321netflix01/|title=Only on Netflix: Premier Horror Suspense Director Eli Roth Reanimates the Gothic Novel With \"Hemlock Grove\"|date=March 21, 2012|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref> Eli Roth serves as an executive producer and will direct the pilot, ''Jellyfish In the Sky''.<ref name=neardeal/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/173201-wondercon-interview-eli-roth-on-hemlock-grove-werewolf-transformation|title=Horror Movies: Reviews, Trailers, News - Shock Till You Drop|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> [[Deran Sarafian]], who signed on in mid-March as an executive producer/series director, directed six episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/hemlock-grove-panel-recap-wondercon/|title=WonderCon 2013: HEMLOCK GROVE Panel Recap Featuring Eli Roth and Famke Janssen|date=March 29, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/03/deran-sarafian-signs-with-wme-joins-hemlock-grove-as-executive-producer/|title=Deran Sarafian Signs With WME, Joins 'Hemlock Grove' As Executive Producer|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=March 16, 2012|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317204545/http://www.deadline.com/2012/03/deran-sarafian-signs-with-wme-joins-hemlock-grove-as-executive-producer/|archive-date=March 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter McGreevy pushed for the series to be filmed in the Pittsburgh area, production was expected to start in early June 2012 and last until November.<ref name=morehemlock>{{cite web|url=http://communityvoices.sites.post-gazette.com/index.php/arts-entertainment-living/tuned-in-journal/32407-more-on-hemlock-grove-the-tv-series|title=More on 'Hemlock Grove,' the TV series|last=Owen|first=Rob|date=March 28, 2012|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|accessdate=July 3, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501032627/http://communityvoices.sites.post-gazette.com/index.php/arts-entertainment-living/tuned-in-journal/32407-more-on-hemlock-grove-the-tv-series|archive-date=May 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=wantedPA>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/tv-radio/author-brian-mcgreevy-pulled-to-have-tv-series-filmed-near-pittsburgh-628400/|title=Author Brian McGreevy pulled to have 'Hemlock Grove' series filmed near Pittsburgh|last=Owen|first=Rob|date=May 9, 2012|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref> In mid May, Gaumont International Television pulled out of Pennsylvania in favor of production at the [[Cinespace Film Studios]] in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://playbackonline.ca/2012/06/04/hemlock-grove-shoot-books-torontos-cinespace-stage|title=Hemlock Grove shoot books Toronto\u2019s Cinespace stage|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|date=June 4, 2012|work=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]]|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> The move came about after Gaumont management had a misunderstanding on how the [[Pennsylvania Film Production Tax Credit|Pennsylvania Film Tax Credit]] program works.<ref name=pullplug>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/tv-radio/tv-series-pulls-plug-on-filming-here-635575/?p=0|title=TV series pulls plug on filming here|date=May 12, 2012|last=Owen|first=Rob|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref> Filming began on July 13, 2012 in [[Port Perry]], [[Ontario]]; a small town about 40 miles (63&nbsp;km) northeast of Toronto that has been transformed to look like Hemlock Grove, the fictional Western Pennsylvania town the series is set in.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1392348--film-crews-to-return-to-port-perry|title=Film crews to return to Port Perry|last=Hall|first=Chris|date=March 16, 2012|work=durhamregion.com|accessdate=July 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401134440/http://www.durhamregion.com/news/article/1392348--film-crews-to-return-to-port-perry|archive-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe budget for the first season of ''Hemlock Grove'' is reportedly about $45 million.<ref name=pullplug/>\n\nFilming took place in Toronto at St Clair and Yonge at the [[Deer Park United Church]] and in [[Hamilton, Ontario]] at [[Hamilton Cemetery]].  Hemlock Grove High School was filmed at [[Ursula Franklin Academy]]/ [[Western Technical Commercial School]] in Toronto.  It was also filmed in [[Oshawa]] at the [[Parkwood Estate]]; the opening scene of Season 1, Episode 1 is on Queen Street in Port Perry, Ontario.\n\n===Casting===\nIn March, Netflix announced that [[Famke Janssen]] and [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] would star in the series, Janssen as Olivia Godfrey and Skarsg\u00e5rd as her son, Roman Godfrey.<ref name=03-21-12/> In early April 2012, it was revealed that Peter Rumancek would be portrayed by [[Landon Liboiron]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/terra-nova-landon-liboiron-netflix-hemlock-grove-eli-roth-307348 |title=Terra Nova's' Landon Liboiron Joins Netflix's 'Hemlock Grove' (Exclusive)|date=April 3, 2012|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> On April 4, Penelope Mitchell was cast as Roman's cousin, Letha Godfrey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/04/series-hemlock-grove-pilots-malibu-country-louis-ckferesten-add-to-casts/|title=Series 'Hemlock Grove', Pilots 'Malibu Country' & Louis CK/Feresten Add To Casts|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=April 2, 2012|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622174605/http://www.deadline.com/2012/04/series-hemlock-grove-pilots-malibu-country-louis-ckferesten-add-to-casts/|archive-date=June 22, 2012}}</ref> Freya Tingley was cast as Christina Wendall on April 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/04/latarsha-rose-cast-in-bets-mary-jane-freya-tingley-in-netflixs-hemlock-grove/|title=Latarsha Rose, Omari Hardwick Join 'Mary Jane'; Freya Tingley To 'Hemlock Grove'|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=April 10, 2012|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622174352/http://www.deadline.com/2012/04/latarsha-rose-cast-in-bets-mary-jane-freya-tingley-in-netflixs-hemlock-grove/|archive-date=June 22, 2012}}</ref> On April 12, [[Dougray Scott]] was announced as Dr. Norman Godfrey, Olivia's brother-in-law and Letha's father.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/04/dougray-scott-to-star-in-netflixs-hemlock-grove/|title=Dougray Scott To Star In Netflix's 'Hemlock Grove'|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=April 12, 2012|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623090441/http://www.deadline.com/2012/04/dougray-scott-to-star-in-netflixs-hemlock-grove/|archive-date=June 23, 2012}}</ref> On July 2, [[Lili Taylor]] was cast as Peter Rumancek's mother, and [[Kandyse McClure]] was cast as Dr. Chasseur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2012/07/02/lili-taylor-hemlock-grove/|title=Exclusive: Six Feet Under Vet Lili Taylor Joins Netflix Thriller Series Hemlock Grove|last=Roots|first=Kimberly|date=July 2, 2012|work=[[TVLine]]|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120704215157/http://tvline.com/2012/07/02/lili-taylor-hemlock-grove/|archive-date=July 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/07/kandyse-mcclure-joins-cast-of-hemlock-grove/|title=Kandyse McClure Joins Cast Of 'Hemlock Grove'|date=July 2, 2012|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120705230949/http://www.deadline.com/2012/07/kandyse-mcclure-joins-cast-of-hemlock-grove/|archive-date=July 5, 2012}}</ref> [[Aaron Douglas (actor)|Aaron Douglas]] was cast as Sheriff Sworn on July 8.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/07/netflix-castings-house-of-cards-hemlock-grove/|title=Netflix Castings: 'House Of Cards', 'Hemlock Grove'|first=The Deadline|last=Team|date=July 8, 2012|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> In late July 2012, [[Kaniehtiio Horn]] joined the cast as Destiny Rumancek.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/hemlock-grove-netflix-tiio-horn-355974 |title='18 to Life' Alum to Play Gypsy Witch-Prostitute on Netflix's 'Hemlock Grove' (Exclusive)|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|date=March 16, 2012|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=July 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe music for seasons 1 and 2 was composed by [[Nathan Barr]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2012/05/29/nathan-barr-to-score-eli-roths-hemlock-grove/|title=Nathan Barr to Score Eli Roth's 'Hemlock Grove'|date=July 8, 2012|work=filmmusicreporter.com|accessdate=July 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603175518/http://filmmusicreporter.com/2012/05/29/nathan-barr-to-score-eli-roths-hemlock-grove/|archive-date=June 3, 2012}}</ref> In October 2015, it was announced that Todd Haberman would join Barr to score season 3.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Todd Haberman Co-Scoring 'Hemlock Grove' Season 3 {{!}} Film Music Reporter|url = http://filmmusicreporter.com/2015/10/20/todd-haberman-co-scoring-hemlock-grove-season-3/|accessdate = 2015-10-20}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Viewership===\nAfter its opening weekend, Netflix announced that \"''Hemlock Grove'' was viewed by more members globally in its first weekend than  ''[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2013/04/22/netflix-hemlock-grove-first-weekend/|title=Netflix says more members watched \u2018Hemlock Grove\u2019 on first weekend than \u2018House of Cards\u2019|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe first season of ''Hemlock Grove'' received \"mixed or average\" reviews, according to [[Metacritic]], with a score of 45 out of 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/hemlock-grove/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for Hemlock Grove Season 1 |publisher=Metacritic |date= |accessdate=2013-07-02}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the season has a rating of 26%, based on 34 reviews, and the average rating is 4.68/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Hemlock Grove'' is an ugly, unpleasant affair that throws crazy ideas together without much forethought.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/hemlock_grove/s01|title=Hemlock Grove: Season 1 - Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe second season received \"generally unfavorable\" reviews, according to Metacritic, with a score of 37 out of 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/hemlock-grove/season-2|title=Hemlock Grove|publisher=|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref> Rotten Tomatoes gives the season a rating of 55%, based on 11 reviews, and the average rating is 5.29/10. The site's consensus reads: \"''Hemlock Grove'' jettisons some of its most grating qualities while doubling down on its splashy gore, making for a more engaging second season \u2013 but the series frustratingly remains a shoddy amalgamation of gothic tropes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/hemlock_grove/s02|title=Hemlock Grove: Season 2 - Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMary McNamara of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called ''Hemlock Grove'' \"terrible\",<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-hemlock-grove-review-netflix-20130419,0,2823333.story | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | last=McNamara | first=Mary | accessdate=April 22, 2013 | date = April 19, 2013 | title=TV review: 'Hemlock Grove' wallows in its own fake guts}}</ref> and Alison Willmore of [[IndieWire]], \"a mess\".<ref>{{cite web | date=April 19, 2013 | accessdate=April 22, 2013 | last=Willmore | first=Alison | url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/hemlock-grove-review-netflix | title=Netflix's New Series 'Hemlock Grove' is a Ramshackle, Sometimes Interesting Mess of Supernatural Themes and Teen Angst | work=[[IndieWire]]}}</ref> Zack Handlen of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave the series an F, calling it \"a shockingly inane misstep, a ponderous mess.\"<ref name=avclub>{{cite web|last=Handlen|first=Zack|title='Hemlock Grove' {{!}} Other Shows {{!}} TV Club|url=https://www.avclub.com/articles/hemlock-grove,96734/|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=April 21, 2013|date=April 20, 2013}}</ref> Dante D'Orazio of ''[[The Verge]]'' said the show was \"universally panned\" on account of its \"poor acting, slow plot development, and ... style that's off-key.\"<ref>{{cite web | last=D'Orazio | first=Dante | work=[[The Verge]] | url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/4/19/4242486/netflix-hemlock-grove-television-series-arrives-today | title=Netflix's 'Hemlock Grove' arrives amidst storm of negative reviews | date=April 19, 2013 | accessdate=April 22, 2013}}</ref>  Patrick Smith of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' said that ''Hemlock Grove'' was \"corny and emphatically less profound than it thinks it is\", giving it two out of five stars overall.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Patrick|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10004169/Hemlock-Grove-Netflix-review.html|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |title=Hemlock Grove, Netflix, review}}</ref> James Poniewozik of ''Time'' listed the series as one of the worst ten things on television in 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/12/17/here-are-10-of-the-worst-things-tv-did-this-year/ | title=Here Are 10 of the Worst Things TV Did This Year | last=Poniewozik | first=James | publisher=Time | date=2013-12-17 | accessdate = 2014-01-01 }}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, David Hiltbrand of the ''Philadelphia Inquirer'' said that the show \"manages to be lush, gross, frightening, and ridiculous--all at the same time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/2013-04-19/news/38649954_1_hemlock-grove-leto-netflix|title=Archives - Philly.com|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> Tom Gliatto of ''People Weekly'' reviewed the series positively, with a score of 75 out of 100: \"The acting is good, especially Bill Skarsgard and Landon Liboiron.... I like the show's languid, dreamlike beauty, but horror fans may be less patient.\" Jessica Shaw of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the series a B+.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2013/04/19/hemlock-grove-netflix-review/|title='Hemlock Grove' review: Gory Netflix series has beating heart|date=April 19, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n''Hemlock Grove'' received two nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music|Outstanding Main Title Theme Music]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Visual Effects]] at the [[65th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/hemlock-grove|title=Hemlock Grove|publisher=|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2013\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[65th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music|Outstanding Original Main Title Theme Music]]\n|[[Nathan Barr]]\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/sites/default/files/2013CreativeArtsEmmysWinners.pdf|title=Creative Arts Emmy Awards Winners|publisher=emmys.com|date=|accessdate=2013-09-15}}</ref> \n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Visual Effects|Outstanding Special Visual Effects]]\n| Episode:\"Children of the Night\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|2014\n|[[Visual Effects Society Awards 2014|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n|Outstanding Visual Effects in a Visual Effects-Driven Photoreal/Live Action Broadcast Program\n|Matt Whelan, Chris Brown<br> Todd Masters, Jonathan Banta<br> Eric McAvoy\n|{{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|first=Erik|last=Pedersen|title=VES Awards 2015: Complete Winners List|url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/ves-awards-winners-2015-visual-effects-society-award-winner-list-1201366460/|accessdate=February 4, 2015|newspaper=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Werewolf fiction]]\n*[[List of vampire television series]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Netflix title}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{Netflix original ended series}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American high school television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American horror television series]]\n[[Category:2013 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2015 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American thriller television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fictional representations of Romani people]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Television series by Gaumont International Television]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Hamilton, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Television about werewolves]]\n", "name_user": "92.2.242.117", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hemlock_Grove_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Stan Laurel", "text_new": "{{short description|English actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Stan Laurel\n| image = Stan Laurel c1920.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = Laurel circa 1920\n| birth_name = Arthur Stanley Jefferson\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1890|06|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ulverston]], [[Lancashire]]<!-- PLEASE do not change to Cumbria: the town was in Lancashire when Laurel was born there -->, England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1965|02|23|1890|06|16|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica, Los Angeles, California]], United States\n| website = {{URL|laurel-and-hardy.com}}\n| occupation = {{hlist|Actor|writer|comedian|entertainer|film director}}\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Lois Neilson]]|1926|1934|end=divorced}}<br>\n{{marriage|Virginia Ruth Rogers|1935|1937|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage||1941|1946|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Vera Ivanova Shuvalova|1938|1940|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Ida Kitaeva Raphael|1946}}\n| domesticpartner = [[Mae Dahlberg|Mae Charlotte Dahlberg]] (1919\u20131925)\n| children = 2\n| signature = Stan Laurel signature.svg\n| years_active = 1906\u20131957\n}}\n\n'''Stan Laurel''' (born '''Arthur Stanley Jefferson'''; 16 June 1890 \u2013 23 February 1965) was an English comic actor, writer, and film director who was part of the comedy duo [[Laurel and Hardy]].<ref>\"Obituary\". ''Variety'', 3 March 1965, p. 69.</ref> He appeared with his comedy partner [[Oliver Hardy]] in 107 short films, feature films, and cameo roles.<ref name=\"Time\"/>\n\nLaurel began his career in [[music hall]], where he developed a number of his standard comic devices, including the [[bowler hat]], the deep comic gravity, and the nonsensical understatement. His performances polished his skills at [[pantomime]] and music hall sketches. He was a member of \"[[Fred Karno]]'s Army\", where he was [[Charlie Chaplin]]'s understudy.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"McCabe\">McCabe 2005, p. 143. Robson, 2005 Retrieved: 18 June 2012.</ref> He and Chaplin arrived in the United States on the same ship from the United Kingdom with the Karno troupe.<ref name=\"Karno\">{{cite web|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/the-fine-mess-maker-at-home/|title=The Fine Mess-Maker at Home|website=New York Times|date=7 September 2012|last=Cavett|first=Dick|access-date=8 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909022128/http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/the-fine-mess-maker-at-home/|archive-date=9 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Laurel began his film career in 1917 and made his final appearance in 1951. He appeared with his comic partner Oliver Hardy in the film short ''[[The Lucky Dog]]'' in 1921, although they did not become an official team until late 1927.<ref name=\"britannica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Laurel-and-Hardy|title=Laurel and Hardy|access-date=18 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418053902/https://www.britannica.com/topic/Laurel-and-Hardy|archive-date=18 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He then appeared exclusively with Hardy until retiring following his comedy partner's death in 1957.\n\nIn 1960, Laurel was given a Lifetime Achievement Academy Award for his pioneering work in comedy, and he has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 7021 Hollywood Blvd. Laurel and Hardy ranked top among best double acts and seventh overall in a 2005 UK poll to find the ''Comedians' Comedian''.<ref name=\"Legacy\"/> In 2019, Laurel topped a list of the greatest British comedians compiled by a panel on the television channel [[Gold (UK TV channel)|Gold]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Stan Laurel crowned Britain's greatest comedian |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2019/05/26/43151/stan_laurel_crowned_britains_greatest_comedian |accessdate=19 October 2019 |work=Chortle.co.uk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019113629/https://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2019/05/26/43151/stan_laurel_crowned_britains_greatest_comedian |archive-date=19 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, a bronze statue of the duo was unveiled in Laurel's home town of [[Ulverston]].\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Ulverston's most famous son - geograph.org.uk - 151570.jpg|thumb|left|Plaque at Laurel's birthplace in [[Ulverston]]]]\nArthur Stanley Jefferson was born in his grandparents' house on 16 June 1890 in Argyll Street, [[Ulverston]], [[Lancashire]]<!-- PLEASE do not change to Cumbria: the town was in Lancashire when Laurel was born there -->, to Arthur Jefferson, a theatre manager from [[Bishop Auckland]], and Margaret (n\u00e9e Metcalfe), an actress from Ulverston. He was one of five children.<ref name=\"ODNB\">Midwinter, Eric. [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/37659 \"Laurel, Stan\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924154506/http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/37659 |date=24 September 2015 }} ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography,'' 2006. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref>\n\nHis parents were both active in the theatre and always very busy. In his early years, Laurel spent much time living with his maternal grandmother, Sarah Metcalfe.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/> He attended school at [[King James I Academy|King James I Grammar School]] in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Stan Laurel's former Bishop Auckland school 'left to rot' | website=[[The Northern Echo]] | date=4 February 2012 | url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/9512813.Stan_Laurel_s_former_Bishop_Auckland_school__left_to_rot_/ | access-date=11 February 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212083244/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/9512813.Stan_Laurel_s_former_Bishop_Auckland_school__left_to_rot_/ | archive-date=12 February 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> and the [[Kings Priory School|King's School]] in [[Tynemouth]], [[Northumberland]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Stan Laurel letter set to go under the hammer | website=[[The Northern Echo]] | date=13 September 2014 | url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/southdurham/bishopauckland/11471926.Stan_Laurel_letter_set_to_go_under_the_hammer/ | access-date=11 February 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212083310/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/southdurham/bishopauckland/11471926.Stan_Laurel_letter_set_to_go_under_the_hammer/ | archive-date=12 February 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Stan Laurel plaque at Britannia Music Hall, Glasgow.jpg|thumb|upright|Stan Laurel plaque, [[Britannia Music Hall]], Glasgow]]\nHe moved with his parents to [[Glasgow]], Scotland, where he completed his education at [[Stonelaw High School|Rutherglen Academy]]. His father managed Glasgow's [[The Metropole Theatre|Metropole Theatre]], where Laurel began work. His boyhood hero was [[Dan Leno]], one of the greatest English [[music hall]] comedians.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/> With a natural affinity for the theatre, Laurel gave his first professional performance on stage at the [[Britannia Music Hall|Panopticon]] in [[Glasgow]] at the age of sixteen, where he polished his skills at [[pantomime]] and music hall sketches.<ref>Bowers 2007, pp. 143\u2013147.</ref> It was the music hall from where he drew his standard comic devices, including his [[bowler hat]] and nonsensical understatement.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/>\n\nIn 1912 Laurel worked together with [[Ted Desmond]]\non tour in Netherlands and Belgium as a comedy double act known as the Barto Bros. Their act, which involved them dressing as Romans, finished when Laurel was offered a spot in an American touring troupe. After Laurel left England for America the pair maintained a life-long friendship, sending letters and photos that documented Laurel\u2019s rise from an unknown British comedy actor in 1913 to one of the biggest names in Hollywood in the 1950s. The correspondence, spanning around 50 years and including photos of them being reunited in the US, was put up for auction by Mr Desmond's grandson Geoffrey Nolan in 2018.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/another-fine-missive-stan-laurel-s-letters-on-sale-6r682sg0d</ref><ref>https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/stan-laurels-little-known-comedy-12098175.amp</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Fred Karno]]'s troupe of actors in 1910 with the stage name of \"Stan Jefferson\"; the troupe also included a young [[Charlie Chaplin]]. The music hall nurtured him, and he acted as Chaplin's [[understudy]] for some time.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"McCabe\"/> Karno was a pioneer of [[slapstick]], and in his biography Laurel stated, \"Fred Karno didn't teach Charlie [Chaplin] and me all we know about comedy. He just taught us most of it\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burton|first1=Alan|title=Pimple, pranks & pratfalls: British film comedy before 1930|date=2000|publisher=Flicks Books|page=51}}</ref> Chaplin and Laurel arrived in the United States on the same ship from Britain with the Karno troupe and toured the country.<ref name=\"Karno\"/>\nDuring the [[First World War]], Laurel registered for military service in America on 5 June 1917, as required under the [[Selective Service Act of 1917|Selective Service Act]]. He was not called up; his registration card states [[Alien (law)|resident alien]] and deafness as exemptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-early-01.html|title=Letters From Stan \u2013 1915\u20131923|first=Bernie|last=Hogya|website=www.lettersfromstan.com|access-date=28 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220140456/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-early-01.html|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebrainydeafsite.com/p3.html|title=P.3|website=TheBrainyDeafSite|access-date=28 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713121725/http://www.thebrainydeafsite.com/p3.html|archive-date=13 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:The Lucky Dog (1921).webm|thumb|left|Laurel and Hardy appeared for the first time together in ''[[The Lucky Dog]]''.]]\n\nThe Karno troupe broke up in the spring of 1914. Stan joined with two other former Karno performers, [[Edgar Hurley]] and his wife Ethel (known as \u201cWren\u201d)to form \u201cThe Three Comiques\u201d.  On the advice of booking agent [[Gordon Bostock]], they call themselves \"the Keystone Trio\". Stan started to do his character as an imitation of Charlie Chaplin, and the Hurleys began to do their parts as silent comedians [[Chester Conklin]] and [[Mabel Normand]]. They played successfully from February through October 1915, until the Hurleys and Stan parted ways.<ref>https://www.cinema.ucla.edu/support/stan-laurels-life-laughter</ref> Between 1916 and 1918, he teamed up with Alice Cooke and [[Baldwin Cooke]], who became his lifelong friends to form the Stan Jefferson Trio.\n\nAmongst other performers, Laurel worked briefly alongside [[Oliver Hardy]] in the silent film short ''[[The Lucky Dog]]'' (1921),<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> before the two were a team. It was around this time that Laurel met [[Mae Dahlberg]]. Around the same time, he adopted the stage name of Laurel at Dahlberg's suggestion that his stage name Stan Jefferson was unlucky, due to it having thirteen letters.{{#tag:ref|Laurel disputed this and claimed that it just \"sounded good\".<ref>McCabe 1961, p. 18.</ref>|group=N}} The pair were performing together when Laurel was offered $75 a week to star in two-reel comedies. After making his first film ''[[Nuts in May (film)|Nuts in May]]'', [[Universal Studios|Universal]] offered him a contract. The contract was soon cancelled during a reorganisation at the studio. Among the films in which Dahlberg and Laurel appeared together was the 1922 parody ''[[Mud and Sand]]''.\n\nBy 1924, Laurel had given up the stage for full-time film work, under contract with [[Joe Rock]] for 12 two-reel comedies. The contract had one unusual stipulation: that Dahlberg was not to appear in any of the films. Rock thought that her temperament was hindering Laurel's career. In 1925, she started interfering with Laurel's work, so Rock offered her a cash settlement and a one-way ticket back to her native [[Australia]], which she accepted.<ref>Bergan 1992, p. 33.</ref> The 12 two-reel comedies were ''[[Mandarin Mix-Up]]'' (1924), ''[[Detained (film)|Detained]]'' (1924), ''[[Monsieur Don't Care]]'' (1924), ''[[West of Hot Dog]]'' (1924), ''[[Somewhere in Wrong]]'' (1925), ''[[Twins (1925 film)|Twins]]'' (1925), ''[[Pie-Eyed]]'' (1925), ''[[The Snow Hawk]]'' (1925), ''[[Navy Blue Days]]'' (1925), ''[[The Sleuth (1925 film)|The Sleuth]]'' (1925), ''[[Dr. Pyckle and Mr. Pryde]]'' (1925) and ''[[Half a Man (film)|Half a Man]]'' (1925).\n\n==Laurel and Hardy==\n{{Main|Laurel and Hardy}}\n[[File:Laurel and Hardy in Lucky Dog.jpg|thumb|left|Laurel with Hardy in ''[[The Lucky Dog (1921 film)|The Lucky Dog]]'' (1921), long before they became a team.]]\nLaurel next signed with the [[Hal Roach]] studio, where he began directing films, including a 1926 production called ''[[Yes, Yes, Nanette]]'' (in which [[Oliver Hardy]] had a part under the name \"Babe\" Hardy). It had been his intention to work primarily as a writer and director.\n\nThe same year, Hardy, a member of the Hal Roach Studios Comedy ''All Star'' players, was injured in a kitchen mishap and hospitalised. Because he was unable to work on the scheduled film, ''Get 'Em Young'', Laurel was asked to return to acting to fill in. Starting early in 1927, Laurel and Hardy began sharing the screen in several short films, including ''[[Duck Soup (1927 film)|Duck Soup]]'', ''[[Slipping Wives]]'' and ''[[With Love and Hisses]]''. The two became friends and their comic chemistry soon became obvious. Roach Studios' supervising director [[Leo McCarey]] noticed the audience reaction to them and began teaming them, leading to the creation of the ''[[Laurel and Hardy]]'' series later that year.\n\nTogether, the two men began producing a huge body of short films, including ''[[The Battle of the Century]]'', ''[[Should Married Men Go Home?]]'', ''[[Two Tars]]'', ''[[Be Big!]]'', ''[[Big Business (1929 film)|Big Business]]'', and many others. Laurel and Hardy successfully made the transition to talking films with the short ''[[Unaccustomed As We Are]]'' in 1929. They also appeared in their first feature in one of the revue sequences of ''[[The Hollywood Revue of 1929]],'' and the following year they appeared as the comic relief in the lavish all-colour (in [[Technicolor]]) musical feature ''[[The Rogue Song]]''. Their first starring feature ''[[Pardon Us]]'' was released in 1931. They continued to make both features and shorts until 1935, including their 1932 three-reeler ''[[The Music Box (film)|The Music Box]],'' which won an [[Academy Award for Live Action Short Film|Academy Award for Best Short Subject]].\n\n===Trouble at Roach Studio===\nDuring the 1930s, Laurel was involved in a dispute with Hal Roach which resulted in the termination of his contract. Roach maintained separate contracts for Laurel and Hardy that expired at different times, so Hardy remained at the studio and was \"teamed\" with [[Harry Langdon]] for the 1939 film ''[[Zenobia (film)|Zenobia]]''. The studio discussed a series of films co-starring Hardy with [[Patsy Kelly]] to be called \"The Hardy Family.\" But Laurel sued Roach over the contract dispute. Eventually, the case was dropped and Laurel returned to Roach. The first film that [[Laurel and Hardy]] made after Laurel returned was ''[[A Chump at Oxford]]''. Subsequently, they made ''[[Saps at Sea]]'', which was their last film for Roach.\n\n===Second World War===\n[[File:Stan in color.jpg|thumb|upright|Stan Laurel in a still from ''[[The Tree in a Test Tube]]'' (1943), a colour short made for the US Department of Agriculture]]\nIn 1941, [[Laurel and Hardy]] signed a contract at [[Twentieth Century-Fox|20th Century-Fox]] to make ten films over five years. Laurel found, to his shock, that he and Hardy were hired only as actors, and were not expected to contribute to the staging, writing, or editing of the productions. When the films proved very successful, Laurel and Hardy were granted more freedom and gradually added more of their own material. They had made six Fox features when the studio suddenly abandoned [[B-picture]] production in December 1944. The team had signed another contract with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] in 1942, resulting in two more features.<ref>[[Scott MacGillivray|MacGillivray, Scott]]. ''Laurel & Hardy: From the Forties Forward''. Second edition: New York: iUniverse, 2009 {{ISBN|978-1440172397}}; first edition: Lanham, Maryland: Vestal Press, 1998.</ref>\n\nRevisiting his [[music hall]] days, Laurel returned to England in 1947 when he and Hardy went on a six-week tour of the United Kingdom performing in [[variety shows]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tea and buns with Laurel and Hardy: Derek Malcolm on the day he met his comedy heroes|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/oct/11/tea-and-buns-with-laurel-and-hardy-the-day-i-met-my-comedy-heroes|accessdate=12 November 2018|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112101245/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/oct/11/tea-and-buns-with-laurel-and-hardy-the-day-i-met-my-comedy-heroes|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Mobbed wherever they went, Laurel's homecoming to [[Ulverston]] took place in May, and the duo were greeted by thousands of fans outside the Coronation Hall.<ref name=\"nwmail\"/> The ''[[North-West Evening Mail|Evening Mail]]'' noted: \"Oliver Hardy remarked to our reporter that Stan had talked about Ulverston for the past 22 years and he thought he had to see it.\"<ref name=\"nwmail\">[http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/stan-at-queen-s-first-royal-variety-show-1.1015949 \"Stan at Queen's first Royal Variety Show\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201221344/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/stan-at-queen-s-first-royal-variety-show-1.1015949 |date=1 February 2014 }}. ''North West Evening Mail''.</ref> The tour included a ''[[Royal Variety Performance]]'' in front of King [[George VI]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]] in London.<ref name=\"nwmail\"/> The success of the tour led them to spend the next seven years touring the UK and Europe.\n\nAround this time, Laurel found out that he had diabetes, so he encouraged Hardy to find solo projects, which he did, taking parts in [[John Wayne]] and [[Bing Crosby]] films.\n\nIn 1950, Laurel and Hardy were invited to France to make a feature film. The film was a disaster, a Franco-Italian co-production titled ''[[Atoll K]]''. (The film was entitled ''Utopia'' in the US and ''Robinson Crusoeland'' in the UK.) Both stars were noticeably ill during the filming. Upon returning to the United States, they spent most of their time recovering. In 1952, Laurel and Hardy toured Europe successfully, and they returned in 1953 for another tour of the continent. During this tour, Laurel fell ill and was unable to perform for several weeks.<ref>Bergen 1992, p. 118.</ref>\n\nIn May 1954, Hardy had a heart attack and cancelled the tour. In 1955, they were planning to do a television series called ''Laurel and Hardy's Fabulous Fables'' based on children's stories. The plans were delayed after Laurel suffered a [[stroke]] on 25 April 1955, from which he recovered. But as the team was planning to get back to work, his partner Hardy had a massive stroke on 14 September 1956, which resulted in his being unable to return to acting.\n\n===Hardy's death===\nOliver Hardy died on 7 August 1957. Laurel was too ill to attend his funeral and said, \"Babe would understand\".<ref name=\"Time\">Rawlngs, Nate. [http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2005073_2005072_2005121,00.html \"Top 10 Across-the-Pond Duos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821083423/http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2005073_2005072_2005121,00.html |date=21 August 2013 }}, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', 20 July 2010. Retrieved: 18 June 2012.</ref>{{dead link|date=January 2020}} People who knew Laurel said that he was devastated by Hardy's death and never fully recovered from it. He refused to perform on stage or act in another film without his friend,<ref name=\"Time\"/> although he continued to socialise with his fans.\n\n==After Laurel and Hardy==\nIn 1961, Stan Laurel was given a Lifetime Achievement Academy Award for his pioneering work in comedy. He had achieved his lifelong dream as a comedian and had been involved in nearly 190 films. He lived his final years in a small flat in the Oceana Apartments in [[Santa Monica, California]].<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_oceana.html \"Latter.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228174300/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_oceana.html |date=28 February 2012 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Archive Project''. Retrieved: 8 September 2012.</ref>\n\nLaurel was always gracious to fans and spent much time answering fan mail. His phone number was listed in the telephone directory, and fans were amazed that they could dial the number and speak to him directly.\n\n[[Jerry Lewis]] was among the numerous comedians to visit Laurel, who offered suggestions for Lewis' production of ''[[The Bellboy]]'' (1960). Lewis paid tribute to Laurel by naming his main character Stanley in the film, and having [[Bill Richmond (writer)|Bill Richmond]] play a version of Laurel as well.<ref>Brody, Richard. [http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/movies/2011/05/jerry-lewis-writer.html \"Front Row: Jerry Lewis, Writer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022103729/http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/movies/2011/05/jerry-lewis-writer.html |date=22 October 2012 }}, ''New Yorker,'' 5 May 2011. Retrieved 17 May 2011.</ref> [[Dick Van Dyke]] told a similar story. When he was just starting his career, he looked up Laurel's phone number, called him, and then visited him at his home. Van Dyke played Laurel on \"The Sam Pomerantz Scandals\" episode of ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]''.\n\nLaurel was offered a cameo role in ''[[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World]]'' (1963), but turned it down. He did not want to be on screen in his old age,<ref name=\"Karno\"/> especially without Hardy. The cameo appearance was then given to [[Jack Benny]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLaurel and [[Mae Dahlberg]] never married but lived together as common-law husband and wife from 1919 to 1925, before Dahlberg accepted a one-way ticket from [[Joe Rock]] to go back to her native Australia.<ref>Simon Louvish, ''Stan and Ollie, The Roots of Comedy'', Faber & Faber 2001 {{ISBN|0-571-21590-4}}</ref> In November 1937, Dahlberg was back in the US and sued Laurel for financial support. At the time, Laurel's second marriage was in the process of a divorce, with Dahlberg's legal suit adding to Laurel's woes. The matter was settled out of court.<ref>[https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19371207.1.4 ''San Bernardino Sun'', Volume 44, 7 December 1937, Page 4, \"Stan Laurels in Agreement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827165914/https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19371207.1.4 |date=27 August 2017 }} Accessed 15 April 2017.</ref> Dahlberg was described as a \"relief project worker\" by the court. Laurel was one of several popular British actors in Hollywood who never became naturalised US citizens.<ref>Prolgue: The Journal of the National Archives, p. 258. Washington, D.C., 1989</ref>\n\nLaurel had four wives and married one of them a second time after their divorce.<ref name=\"latimes.com\">Harnisch, Larry. [http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-then21-2009jun21,0,3596284.story?track=rss \"Stan Laurel's stormy marriage full of off-screen drama.\"] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', 21 June 2009. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> His first wife was [[Lois Neilson]], whom he married on 13 August 1926. Their daughter Lois was born on 10 December 1927 during the early years of Laurel and Hardy's partnership. In May 1930, their son Stanley was born two months premature and died after nine days. Laurel's daughter Lois died on 27 July 2017, aged 89.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lois-laurel-hawes-dead-stan-laurels-daughter-was-89-1025214 |title=Lois Laurel Hawes, Daughter of Stan Laurel, Dies at 89 |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809173457/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lois-laurel-hawes-dead-stan-laurels-daughter-was-89-1025214 |archive-date=9 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Laurel and Neilson divorced in December 1934.\n\nIn 1935, Laurel married Virginia Ruth Rogers (known as Ruth). In 1937, he filed for divorce, confessing that he was not over his ex-wife Lois, but Lois decided against a reconciliation. On New Year's Day 1938, Laurel married Vera Ivanova Shuvalova (known as Illeana), and Ruth accused him of bigamy, but their divorce had been finalised a couple of days before his new marriage. The new marriage was very volatile, and Illeana accused him of trying to bury her alive in the backyard of their San Fernando Valley home.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harnisch|first1=Larry|title=Stormy marriage full of off-screen drama for Stan Laurel|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/21/local/me-then21|accessdate=14 April 2018|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=21 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726193035/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/21/local/me-then21|archive-date=26 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He and Illeana separated in 1939 and divorced in 1940, with Illeana surrendering all claim to the Laurel surname on 1 February 1940 in exchange for $6,500.<ref>Associated Press, \"Surrenders Her Name\", ''The Spokesman-Review'', Spokane, Washington, Friday 2 February 1940, Volume 57, Number 264, page 2.</ref> In 1941, Laurel remarried Virginia Ruth Rogers; they were divorced for the second time in early 1946.<ref name=\"latimes.com\"/> On 6 May 1946, he married Ida Kitaeva Raphael to whom he remained married until his death.<ref name=\"latimes.com\"/>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Laurel grave.JPG|thumb|right|Stan Laurel's grave at Forest Lawn]]\nLaurel was a heavy smoker until suddenly quitting around 1960.<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1964-04.html \"Correspondence: April 4\u201329, 1964.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711221112/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1964-04.html |date=11 July 2018 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Project'' via ''lettersfromstan.com.'' Retrieved: 29 September 2018.</ref> In January 1965, he underwent a series of x-rays for an infection on the roof of his mouth.<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1965-01.html \"Correspondence: January 4\u201329, 1965.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903154327/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_1965-01.html |date=3 September 2011 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Project'' via ''lettersfromstan.com.'' Retrieved: 10 August 2011.</ref> He died on 23 February 1965, aged 74, four days after suffering a heart attack on 19 February.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1965/02/24/archives/stan-laurel-dies-i-movie-comedian-teamed-with-oliver-hardy-in-200.html \"Stan Laurel Dies. Teamed With Oliver Hardy in 200 Slapstick Films-Played 'Simple' Foil.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723214640/https://www.nytimes.com/1965/02/24/archives/stan-laurel-dies-i-movie-comedian-teamed-with-oliver-hardy-in-200.html |date=23 July 2018 }} ''The New York Times'', 24 February 1965. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> Minutes before his death, he told his nurse that he would not mind going skiing, and she replied that she was not aware that he was a skier. \"I'm not,\" said Laurel, \"I'd rather be doing that than this!\" A few minutes later he died quietly in his armchair.<ref>Bergen 1992, pp. 119\u2013120.</ref>\n\nAt his funeral, [[Buster Keaton]] said, \"[[Charlie Chaplin|Chaplin]] wasn't the funniest. I wasn't the funniest; this man was the funniest.\" [[Dick Van Dyke]] gave the eulogy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTw0TPv6n1s|title=Raw footage of Stan Laurels funeral with Dick Van Dyke, Buster Keaton and more|last=ebonyivorymovies|date=2 January 2014|via=YouTube|access-date=12 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609174226/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTw0TPv6n1s|archive-date=9 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> as a friend, prot\u00e9g\u00e9, and occasional impressionist of Laurel during his later years; he read \"[[The Clown's Prayer]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZRvfn1BCoHwC&pg=PT141&lpg=PT141&dq=Dick+Van+Dyke+a+prayer+for+clowns&source=bl&ots=f-0S_HsdgQ&sig=a3U2zAnu47IevPc7L1CqovPwM0M&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9_dDlrdbQAhUFwiYKHfEHB1sQ6AEIPzAG#v=onepage&q=Dick+Van+Dyke+a+prayer+for+clowns&f=false|title=My Lucky Life in and Out of Show Business: A Memoir|first=Dick Van|last=Dyke|date=3 May 2011|publisher=Crown/Archetype|via=Google Books}}</ref> Laurel had quipped, \"If anyone at my funeral has a long face, I'll never speak to him again.\"<ref name=\"Legacy\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=-h3-oAEoQMYC&pg=PA95 \"The Making of Stan Laurel: Echoes of a British Boyhood\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627191441/http://books.google.com/books?id=-h3-oAEoQMYC&pg=PA95 |date=27 June 2014 }}, p. 95. McFarland, 2011.</ref> He was interred in [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)|Forest Lawn\u2013Hollywood Hills Cemetery]].<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d ed.: 2 (Kindle Locations 26901-26907). McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers. Kindle Edition.</ref>\n\n==Legacy and honours==\n[[File:Statues of Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Statue of Stan Laurel and [[Oliver Hardy]] outside the Coronation Hall, [[Ulverston]], Cumbria, England]]\nLaurel and Hardy are featured on the cover of [[the Beatles]]' 1967 album ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]''.<ref>Levy 2005, p. 5.</ref> In 1989, a statue of Laurel was erected in Dockwray Square, [[North Shields]], [[Tyne and Wear]], England, where he lived at No. 8 from 1897 to 1902. The steps down from the Square to the North Shields Fish Quay were said to have inspired the piano-moving scene in ''[[The Music Box]]''. In a 2005 UK poll, ''Comedians' Comedian'', Laurel and Hardy were ranked top double act, and seventh overall.<ref name=\"Legacy\"/> Along with Hardy, Laurel was inducted into the [[Grand Order of Water Rats]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gowr.co.uk/roll-of-honour/ |title= Roll of Honour |publisher= Grand Order of Water Rats |accessdate= 17 April 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170418162039/http://www.gowr.co.uk/roll-of-honour/ |archive-date= 18 April 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n[[File:Stan Laurel Statue, Bishop Auckland.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Statue of Laurel on the site once occupied by the theatre owned by his parents, in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]], north east England]]\n[[Neil Brand]] wrote a radio play entitled ''[[Stan (play)|Stan]]'', broadcast in 2004 on [[BBC Radio 4]] and subsequently on [[BBC Radio 4 Extra]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0076mjl|title=Neil Brand - Stan - BBC Radio 4 Extra|website=BBC|access-date=25 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401162050/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0076mjl|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> starring [[Tom Courtenay]] as Stan Laurel, in which Stan visits Oliver Hardy after Hardy has suffered his stroke and tries to say the things to his dying friend and partner that have been left unsaid. In 2006, [[BBC Four]] showed a drama called ''Stan'', based on Brand's radio play, in which Laurel meets Hardy on his deathbed and reminisces about their career.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/cinema/features/silent-cinema-season.shtml \"BBC Four Cinema - Silent Cinema Season.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060624173712/http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/cinema/features/silent-cinema-season.shtml |date=24 June 2006 }} ''BBC''. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref>\n\nA plaque on the Bull Inn, [[Bottesford, Leicestershire]], England, marks Laurel and Hardy appearing in [[Nottingham]] over Christmas 1952, and staying with Laurel's sister, Olga, who was the landlady of the pub.<ref>[http://leicestershire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/the-battle-for-bottesford-the-border-town-of-nottinghamshire-and-leicestershire-23520/ \"The Battle for Bottesford \u2013 the border town of Nottinghamshire and Leicestershire.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207081335/http://leicestershire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/the-battle-for-bottesford-the-border-town-of-nottinghamshire-and-leicestershire-23520 |date=7 December 2010 }} ''Leicestershire Magazine'', 31 July 2010. Retrieved: 6 October 2010.</ref> In 2008, a statue of Stan Laurel was unveiled in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]], on the site of the Eden Theatre.<ref>Roberts, Will. [http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/3590723.Laurel_proves_Hardy_after_disaster_delays \"Laurel proves Hardy after disaster delays: Statue of Laurel arrives in Bishop Auckland.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005121533/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/3590723.Laurel_proves_Hardy_after_disaster_delays/ |date=5 October 2012 }} ''thenorthernecho'', 13 August 2008. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> In April 2009, a bronze statue of Laurel and Hardy was unveiled in Ulverston.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/8006614.stm \"Statue honours Laurel and Hardy.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420073138/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/8006614.stm |date=20 April 2009 }} ''BBC'', 19 April 2009. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/5183293/Hundreds-attend-Laurel-and-Hardy-statue-unveiling.html \"Hundreds attend Laurel and Hardy statue unveiling\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225221216/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/5183293/Hundreds-attend-Laurel-and-Hardy-statue-unveiling.html |date=25 December 2017 }}, ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved: 25 July 2012.</ref>\n\n[[File:Laurel and hardy autocorrect.JPG|thumb|upright|Laurel & Hardy Museum in Ulverston]]\nThere is a Laurel and Hardy Museum in Stan's hometown of Ulverston. There are two Laurel and Hardy museums in Hardy's hometown of [[Harlem, Georgia|Harlem]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. One is operated by the town of Harlem, and the other is a private museum owned and operated by Gary Russeth, a Harlem resident.\n\nIn 2013 [[Gail Louw]] and [[Jeffrey Holland (actor)|Jeffrey Holland]] debuted a short one-man play \"...And this is my friend Mr Laurel\" at the [[Camden Fringe]] festival. The play, starring Holland as Laurel, was taken on tour of the UK in 2014 until June 2015.<ref>[http://www.jeffreyholland.co.uk/Jeffrey_Holland/Mr_Laurel.html \"'...And this is my friend Mr Laurel'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306222553/http://www.jeffreyholland.co.uk/Jeffrey_Holland/Mr_Laurel.html |date=6 March 2015 }}, ''jeffreyholland.co.uk''. Retrieved: 2 March 2015.</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 film ''[[Stan & Ollie]]'', [[Steve Coogan]] portrayed Laurel (a performance which saw him nominated for the [[BAFTA Awards|BAFTA]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]]) and [[John C. Reilly]] played Hardy.<ref name=\"Stan & Ollie\">{{cite news|title=Steve Coogan and John C. Reilly will be Laurel and Hardy in Stan & Ollie|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/steve-coogan-john-c-reilly-will-laurel-hardy-stan-ollie/|publisher=Empire magazine|date=18 January 2016|access-date=19 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105173949/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/steve-coogan-john-c-reilly-will-laurel-hardy-stan-ollie/|archive-date=5 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Developed by [[BBC Films]], the film is set in the twilight of their careers, and focuses on their farewell tour of Britain and Ireland's [[variety show|variety]] halls in 1953.\n\n==Filmography==\n* [[Stan Laurel filmography]] (films of Stan Laurel as an actor without Oliver Hardy)\n* [[Laurel and Hardy filmography]] (filmography of Laurel and Hardy together)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|Biography|Comedy|Film}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=N}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* Bergen, Ronald. ''The Life and Times of Laurel and Hardy.'' New York: Smithmark, 1992. {{ISBN|0-8317-5459-1}}.\n* Bowers, Judith. ''Stan Laurel and Other Stars of the Panopticon: The Story of the Britannia Music Hall''. Edinburgh: Birlinn Ltd, 2007. {{ISBN|1-84158-617-X}}.\n* Louvish, Simon. ''Stan and Ollie: The Roots of Comedy''. London: Faber & Faber, 2001. {{ISBN|0-571-21590-4}}.\n* Marriot, A. J. ''Laurel & Hardy: The British Tours''. Hitchen, Herts, UK: AJ Marriot, 1993. {{ISBN|0-9521308-0-7}}.\n* Levy, Joe, ed. ''Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time''. New York: Wenner Books, 2005. {{ISBN|978-1-932958-61-4}}.\n* [[John McCabe (writer)|McCabe, John]]. ''Babe: The Life of Oliver Hardy''. London: Robson Books Ltd., 2004. {{ISBN|1-86105-781-4}}.\n* McCabe, John. ''Comedy World of Stan Laurel''. London: Robson Books, 2005, First edition 1975. {{ISBN|978-1-86105-780-8}}.\n* McCabe, John. ''Mr. Laurel & Mr. Hardy: An Affectionate Biography.'' London: Robson Books, 2004, First edition 1961, {{ISBN|1-86105-606-0}}.\n* Stone, Rob. ''Laurel or Hardy: The Solo Films of Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy.'' Temecula, California: Split Reel Books, 1996\n* Okuda, Ted, and James L. Neibaur. ''Stan Without Ollie: The Stan Laurel Solo Films.'' Jefferson, NC: McFarland and Co., 2012\n* Guiles, Fred Lawrence. ''Stan: The Life of Stan Laurel''. New York: Stein and Day., 1980\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Stan Laurel |sopt=t}}\n* {{IMDb name|0491048}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=109430|name=Stan Laurel}}\n* ''[http://www.brentonfilm.com/articles/the-making-of-stan-laurel-echoes-of-a-british-boyhood The Making of Stan Laurel: Echoes of a British Boyhood]'' article at [http://www.brentonfilm.com/ Brenton Film] by Danny Lawrence, Stan Laurel's biographer\n* [http://www.laurel-and-hardy-museum.co.uk/ Laurel and Hardy Museum, Ulverston]\n* [http://www.lettersfromstan.com/ The Stan Laurel Correspondence Archive Project]\n\n{{Laurel and Hardy}}\n{{Academy Honorary Award}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward LifeAchievement 1960\u20131979}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laurel, Stan}}\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:Laurel and Hardy|*]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Lancashire]]\n[[Category:British male comedy actors]]\n[[Category:English entertainers]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male silent film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English stunt performers]]\n[[Category:Grand Order of Water Rats members]]\n[[Category:Music hall performers]]\n[[Category:Silent film comedians]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Academy Honorary Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Screen Actors Guild Life Achievement Award]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:Hal Roach Studios actors]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer contract players]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:British expatriate male actors in the United States]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Tynemouth]]\n[[Category:People educated at Stonelaw High School]]\n[[Category:People from Ulverston]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:19th-century English people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English comedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Stan Laurel\n| image = Stan Laurel c1920.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = Laurel circa 1920\n| birth_name = Arthur Stanley Jefferson\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1890|06|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ulverston]], [[Lancashire]]<!-- PLEASE do not change to Cumbria: the town was in Lancashire when Laurel was born there -->, England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1965|02|23|1890|06|16|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica, Los Angeles, California]], United States\n| website = {{URL|laurel-and-hardy.com}}\n| occupation = {{hlist|Actor|writer|comedian|entertainer|film director}}\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Lois Neilson]]|1926|1934|end=divorced}}<br>\n{{marriage|Virginia Ruth Rogers|1935|1937|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage||1941|1946|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Vera Ivanova Shuvalova|1938|1940|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Ida Kitaeva Raphael|1946}}\n| domesticpartner = [[Mae Dahlberg|Mae Charlotte Dahlberg]] (1919\u20131925)\n| children = 2\n| signature = Stan Laurel signature.svg\n| years_active = 1906\u20131957\n}}\n\n'''Stan Laurel''' (born '''Arthur Stanley Jefferson'''; 16 June 1890 \u2013 23 February 1965) was an English comic actor, writer, and film director who was part of the comedy duo [[Laurel and Hardy]].<ref>\"Obituary\". ''Variety'', 3 March 1965, p. 69.</ref> He appeared with his comedy partner [[Oliver Hardy]] in 107 short films, feature films, and cameo roles.<ref name=\"Time\"/>\n\nLaurel began his career in [[music hall]], where he developed a number of his standard comic devices, including the [[bowler hat]], the deep comic gravity, and the nonsensical understatement. His performances polished his skills at [[pantomime]] and music hall sketches. He was a member of \"[[Fred Karno]]'s Army\", where he was [[Charlie Chaplin]]'s understudy.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"McCabe\">McCabe 2005, p. 143. Robson, 2005 Retrieved: 18 June 2012.</ref> He and Chaplin arrived in the United States on the same ship from the United Kingdom with the Karno troupe.<ref name=\"Karno\">{{cite web|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/the-fine-mess-maker-at-home/|title=The Fine Mess-Maker at Home|website=New York Times|date=7 September 2012|last=Cavett|first=Dick|access-date=8 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909022128/http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/the-fine-mess-maker-at-home/|archive-date=9 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Laurel began his film career in 1917 and made his final appearance in 1951. He appeared with his comic partner Oliver Hardy in the film short ''[[The Lucky Dog]]'' in 1921, although they did not become an official team until late 1927.<ref name=\"britannica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Laurel-and-Hardy|title=Laurel and Hardy|access-date=18 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418053902/https://www.britannica.com/topic/Laurel-and-Hardy|archive-date=18 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He then appeared exclusively with Hardy until retiring following his comedy partner's death in 1957.\n\nIn 1960, Laurel was given a Lifetime Achievement Academy Award for his pioneering work in comedy, and he has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 7021 Hollywood Blvd. Laurel and Hardy ranked top among best double acts and seventh overall in a 2005 UK poll to find the ''Comedians' Comedian''.<ref name=\"Legacy\"/> In 2019, Laurel topped a list of the greatest British comedians compiled by a panel on the television channel [[Gold (UK TV channel)|Gold]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Stan Laurel crowned Britain's greatest comedian |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2019/05/26/43151/stan_laurel_crowned_britains_greatest_comedian |accessdate=19 October 2019 |work=Chortle.co.uk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019113629/https://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2019/05/26/43151/stan_laurel_crowned_britains_greatest_comedian |archive-date=19 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, a bronze statue of the duo was unveiled in Laurel's home town of [[Ulverston]].\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Ulverston's most famous son - geograph.org.uk - 151570.jpg|thumb|left|Plaque at Laurel's birthplace in [[Ulverston]]]]\nArthur Stanley Jefferson was born in his grandparents' house on 16 June 1890 in Argyll Street, [[Ulverston]], [[Lancashire]]<!-- PLEASE do not change to Cumbria: the town was in Lancashire when Laurel was born there -->, to Arthur Jefferson, a theatre manager from [[Bishop Auckland]], and Margaret (n\u00e9e Metcalfe), an actress from Ulverston. He was one of five children.<ref name=\"ODNB\">Midwinter, Eric. [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/37659 \"Laurel, Stan\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924154506/http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/37659 |date=24 September 2015 }} ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography,'' 2006. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref>\n\nHis parents were both active in the theatre and always very busy. In his early years, Laurel spent much time living with his maternal grandmother, Sarah Metcalfe.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/> He attended school at [[King James I Academy|King James I Grammar School]] in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Stan Laurel's former Bishop Auckland school 'left to rot' | website=[[The Northern Echo]] | date=4 February 2012 | url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/9512813.Stan_Laurel_s_former_Bishop_Auckland_school__left_to_rot_/ | access-date=11 February 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212083244/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/9512813.Stan_Laurel_s_former_Bishop_Auckland_school__left_to_rot_/ | archive-date=12 February 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> and the [[Kings Priory School|King's School]] in [[Tynemouth]], [[Northumberland]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Stan Laurel letter set to go under the hammer | website=[[The Northern Echo]] | date=13 September 2014 | url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/southdurham/bishopauckland/11471926.Stan_Laurel_letter_set_to_go_under_the_hammer/ | access-date=11 February 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212083310/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/southdurham/bishopauckland/11471926.Stan_Laurel_letter_set_to_go_under_the_hammer/ | archive-date=12 February 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Stan Laurel plaque at Britannia Music Hall, Glasgow.jpg|thumb|upright|Stan Laurel plaque, [[Britannia Music Hall]], Glasgow]]\nHe moved with his parents to [[Glasgow]], Scotland, where he completed his education at [[Stonelaw High School|Rutherglen Academy]]. His father managed Glasgow's [[The Metropole Theatre|Metropole Theatre]], where Laurel began work. His boyhood hero was [[Dan Leno]], one of the greatest English [[music hall]] comedians.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/> With a natural affinity for the theatre, Laurel gave his first professional performance on stage at the [[Britannia Music Hall|Panopticon]] in [[Glasgow]] at the age of sixteen, where he polished his skills at [[pantomime]] and music hall sketches.<ref>Bowers 2007, pp. 143\u2013147.</ref> It was the music hall from where he drew his standard comic devices, including his [[bowler hat]] and nonsensical understatement.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/>\n\nIn 1912 Laurel worked together with [[Ted Desmond]]\non tour in Netherlands and Belgium as a comedy double act known as the Barto Bros. Their act, which involved them dressing as Romans, finished when Laurel was offered a spot in an American touring troupe. After Laurel left England for America the pair maintained a life-long friendship, sending letters and photos that documented Laurel\u2019s rise from an unknown British comedy actor in 1913 to one of the biggest names in Hollywood in the 1950s. The correspondence, spanning around 50 years and including photos of them being reunited in the US, was put up for auction by Mr Desmond's grandson Geoffrey Nolan in 2018.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/another-fine-missive-stan-laurel-s-letters-on-sale-6r682sg0d</ref><ref>https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/stan-laurels-little-known-comedy-12098175.amp</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Fred Karno]]'s troupe of actors in 1910 with the stage name of \"Stan Jefferson\"; the troupe also included a young [[Charlie Chaplin]]. The music hall nurtured him, and he acted as Chaplin's [[understudy]] for some time.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"McCabe\"/> Karno was a pioneer of [[slapstick]], and in his biography Laurel stated, \"Fred Karno didn't teach Charlie [Chaplin] and me all we know about comedy. He just taught us most of it\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burton|first1=Alan|title=Pimple, pranks & pratfalls: British film comedy before 1930|date=2000|publisher=Flicks Books|page=51}}</ref> Chaplin and Laurel arrived in the United States on the same ship from Britain with the Karno troupe and toured the country.<ref name=\"Karno\"/>\nDuring the [[First World War]], Laurel registered for military service in America on 5 June 1917, as required under the [[Selective Service Act of 1917|Selective Service Act]]. He was not called up; his registration card states [[Alien (law)|resident alien]] and deafness as exemptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-early-01.html|title=Letters From Stan \u2013 1915\u20131923|first=Bernie|last=Hogya|website=www.lettersfromstan.com|access-date=28 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220140456/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-early-01.html|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebrainydeafsite.com/p3.html|title=P.3|website=TheBrainyDeafSite|access-date=28 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713121725/http://www.thebrainydeafsite.com/p3.html|archive-date=13 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:The Lucky Dog (1921).webm|thumb|left|Laurel and Hardy appeared for the first time together in ''[[The Lucky Dog]]''.]]\n\nThe Karno troupe broke up in the spring of 1914. Stan joined with two other former Karno performers, [[Edgar Hurley]] and his wife Ethel (known as \u201cWren\u201d)to form \u201cThe Three Comiques\u201d.  On the advice of booking agent [[Gordon Bostock]], they call themselves \"the Keystone Trio\". Stan started to do his character as an imitation of Charlie Chaplin, and the Hurleys began to do their parts as silent comedians [[Chester Conklin]] and [[Mabel Normand]]. They played successfully from February through October 1915, until the Hurleys and Stan parted ways.<ref>https://www.cinema.ucla.edu/support/stan-laurels-life-laughter</ref> Between 1916 and 1918, he teamed up with Alice Cooke and [[Baldwin Cooke]], who became his lifelong friends to form the Stan Jefferson Trio.\n\nAmongst other performers, Laurel worked briefly alongside [[Oliver Hardy]] in the silent film short ''[[The Lucky Dog]]'' (1921),<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> before the two were a team. It was around this time that Laurel met [[Mae Dahlberg]]. Around the same time, he adopted the stage name of Laurel at Dahlberg's suggestion that his stage name Stan Jefferson was unlucky, due to it having thirteen letters.{{#tag:ref|Laurel disputed this and claimed that it just \"sounded good\".<ref>McCabe 1961, p. 18.</ref>|group=N}} The pair were performing together when Laurel was offered $75 a week to star in two-reel comedies. After making his first film ''[[Nuts in May (film)|Nuts in May]]'', [[Universal Studios|Universal]] offered him a contract. The contract was soon cancelled during a reorganisation at the studio. Among the films in which Dahlberg and Laurel appeared together was the 1922 parody ''[[Mud and Sand]]''.\n\nBy 1924, Laurel had given up the stage for full-time film work, under contract with [[Joe Rock]] for 12 two-reel comedies. The contract had one unusual stipulation: that Dahlberg was not to appear in any of the films. Rock thought that her temperament was hindering Laurel's career. In 1925, she started interfering with Laurel's work, so Rock offered her a cash settlement and a one-way ticket back to her native [[Australia]], which she accepted.<ref>Bergan 1992, p. 33.</ref> The 12 two-reel comedies were ''[[Mandarin Mix-Up]]'' (1924), ''[[Detained (film)|Detained]]'' (1924), ''[[Monsieur Don't Care]]'' (1924), ''[[West of Hot Dog]]'' (1924), ''[[Somewhere in Wrong]]'' (1925), ''[[Twins (1925 film)|Twins]]'' (1925), ''[[Pie-Eyed]]'' (1925), ''[[The Snow Hawk]]'' (1925), ''[[Navy Blue Days]]'' (1925), ''[[The Sleuth (1925 film)|The Sleuth]]'' (1925), ''[[Dr. Pyckle and Mr. Pryde]]'' (1925) and ''[[Half a Man (film)|Half a Man]]'' (1925).\n\n==Laurel and Hardy==\n{{Main|Laurel and Hardy}}\n[[File:Laurel and Hardy in Lucky Dog.jpg|thumb|left|Laurel with Hardy in ''[[The Lucky Dog (1921 film)|The Lucky Dog]]'' (1921), long before they became a team.]]\nLaurel next signed with the [[Hal Roach]] studio, where he began directing films, including a 1926 production called ''[[Yes, Yes, Nanette]]'' (in which [[Oliver Hardy]] had a part under the name \"Babe\" Hardy). It had been his intention to work primarily as a writer and director.\n\nThe same year, Hardy, a member of the Hal Roach Studios Comedy ''All Star'' players, was injured in a kitchen mishap and hospitalised. Because he was unable to work on the scheduled film, ''Get 'Em Young'', Laurel was asked to return to acting to fill in. Starting early in 1927, Laurel and Hardy began sharing the screen in several short films, including ''[[Duck Soup (1927 film)|Duck Soup]]'', ''[[Slipping Wives]]'' and ''[[With Love and Hisses]]''. The two became friends and their comic chemistry soon became obvious. Roach Studios' supervising director [[Leo McCarey]] noticed the audience reaction to them and began teaming them, leading to the creation of the ''[[Laurel and Hardy]]'' series later that year.\n\nTogether, the two men began producing a huge body of short films, including ''[[The Battle of the Century]]'', ''[[Should Married Men Go Home?]]'', ''[[Two Tars]]'', ''[[Be Big!]]'', ''[[Big Business (1929 film)|Big Business]]'', and many others. Laurel and Hardy successfully made the transition to talking films with the short ''[[Unaccustomed As We Are]]'' in 1929. They also appeared in their first feature in one of the revue sequences of ''[[The Hollywood Revue of 1929]],'' and the following year they appeared as the comic relief in the lavish all-colour (in [[Technicolor]]) musical feature ''[[The Rogue Song]]''. Their first starring feature ''[[Pardon Us]]'' was released in 1931. They continued to make both features and shorts until 1935, including their 1932 three-reeler ''[[The Music Box (film)|The Music Box]],'' which won an [[Academy Award for Live Action Short Film|Academy Award for Best Short Subject]].\n\n===Trouble at Roach Studio===\nDuring the 1930s, Laurel was involved in a dispute with Hal Roach which resulted in the termination of his contract. Roach maintained separate contracts for Laurel and Hardy that expired at different times, so Hardy remained at the studio and was \"teamed\" with [[Harry Langdon]] for the 1939 film ''[[Zenobia (film)|Zenobia]]''. The studio discussed a series of films co-starring Hardy with [[Patsy Kelly]] to be called \"The Hardy Family.\" But Laurel sued Roach over the contract dispute. Eventually, the case was dropped and Laurel returned to Roach. The first film that [[Laurel and Hardy]] made after Laurel returned was ''[[A Chump at Oxford]]''. Subsequently, they made ''[[Saps at Sea]]'', which was their last film for Roach.\n\n===Second World War===\n[[File:Stan in color.jpg|thumb|upright|Stan Laurel in a still from ''[[The Tree in a Test Tube]]'' (1943), a colour short made for the US Department of Agriculture]]\nIn 1941, [[Laurel and Hardy]] signed a contract at [[Twentieth Century-Fox|20th Century-Fox]] to make ten films over five years. Laurel found, to his shock, that he and Hardy were hired only as actors, and were not expected to contribute to the staging, writing, or editing of the productions. When the films proved very successful, Laurel and Hardy were granted more freedom and gradually added more of their own material. They had made six Fox features when the studio suddenly abandoned [[B-picture]] production in December 1944. The team had signed another contract with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] in 1942, resulting in two more features.<ref>[[Scott MacGillivray|MacGillivray, Scott]]. ''Laurel & Hardy: From the Forties Forward''. Second edition: New York: iUniverse, 2009 {{ISBN|978-1440172397}}; first edition: Lanham, Maryland: Vestal Press, 1998.</ref>\n\nRevisiting his [[music hall]] days, Laurel returned to England in 1947 when he and Hardy went on a six-week tour of the United Kingdom performing in [[variety shows]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tea and buns with Laurel and Hardy: Derek Malcolm on the day he met his comedy heroes|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/oct/11/tea-and-buns-with-laurel-and-hardy-the-day-i-met-my-comedy-heroes|accessdate=12 November 2018|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112101245/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/oct/11/tea-and-buns-with-laurel-and-hardy-the-day-i-met-my-comedy-heroes|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Mobbed wherever they went, Laurel's homecoming to [[Ulverston]] took place in May, and the duo were greeted by thousands of fans outside the Coronation Hall.<ref name=\"nwmail\"/> The ''[[North-West Evening Mail|Evening Mail]]'' noted: \"Oliver Hardy remarked to our reporter that Stan had talked about Ulverston for the past 22 years and he thought he had to see it.\"<ref name=\"nwmail\">[http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/stan-at-queen-s-first-royal-variety-show-1.1015949 \"Stan at Queen's first Royal Variety Show\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201221344/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/stan-at-queen-s-first-royal-variety-show-1.1015949 |date=1 February 2014 }}. ''North West Evening Mail''.</ref> The tour included a ''[[Royal Variety Performance]]'' in front of King [[George VI]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]] in London.<ref name=\"nwmail\"/> The success of the tour led them to spend the next seven years touring the UK and Europe.\n\nAround this time, Laurel found out that he had diabetes, so he encouraged Hardy to find solo projects, which he did, taking parts in [[John Wayne]] and [[Bing Crosby]] films.\n\nIn 1950, Laurel and Hardy were invited to France to make a feature film. The film was a disaster, a Franco-Italian co-production titled ''[[Atoll K]]''. (The film was entitled ''Utopia'' in the US and ''Robinson Crusoeland'' in the UK.) Both stars were noticeably ill during the filming. Upon returning to the United States, they spent most of their time recovering. In 1952, Laurel and Hardy toured Europe successfully, and they returned in 1953 for another tour of the continent. During this tour, Laurel fell ill and was unable to perform for several weeks.<ref>Bergen 1992, p. 118.</ref>\n\nIn May 1954, Hardy had a heart attack and cancelled the tour. In 1955, they were planning to do a television series called ''Laurel and Hardy's Fabulous Fables'' based on children's stories. The plans were delayed after Laurel suffered a [[stroke]] on 25 April 1955, from which he recovered. But as the team was planning to get back to work, his partner Hardy had a massive stroke on 14 September 1956, which resulted in his being unable to return to acting.\n\n===Hardy's death===\nOliver Hardy died on 7 August 1957. Laurel was too ill to attend his funeral and said, \"Babe would understand\".<ref name=\"Time\">Rawlngs, Nate. [http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2005073_2005072_2005121,00.html \"Top 10 Across-the-Pond Duos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821083423/http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2005073_2005072_2005121,00.html |date=21 August 2013 }}, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', 20 July 2010. Retrieved: 18 June 2012.</ref>{{dead link|date=January 2020}} People who knew Laurel said that he was devastated by Hardy's death and never fully recovered from it. He refused to perform on stage or act in another film without his friend,<ref name=\"Time\"/> although he continued to socialise with his fans.\n\n==After Laurel and Hardy==\nIn 1961, Stan Laurel was given a Lifetime Achievement Academy Award for his pioneering work in comedy. He had achieved his lifelong dream as a comedian and had been involved in nearly 190 films. He lived his final years in a small flat in the Oceana Apartments in [[Santa Monica, California]].<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_oceana.html \"Latter.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228174300/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_oceana.html |date=28 February 2012 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Archive Project''. Retrieved: 8 September 2012.</ref>\n\nLaurel was always gracious to fans and spent much time answering fan mail. His phone number was listed in the telephone directory, and fans were amazed that they could dial the number and speak to him directly.\n\n[[Jerry Lewis]] was among the numerous comedians to visit Laurel, who offered suggestions for Lewis' production of ''[[The Bellboy]]'' (1960). Lewis paid tribute to Laurel by naming his main character Stanley in the film, and having [[Bill Richmond (writer)|Bill Richmond]] play a version of Laurel as well.<ref>Brody, Richard. [http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/movies/2011/05/jerry-lewis-writer.html \"Front Row: Jerry Lewis, Writer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022103729/http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/movies/2011/05/jerry-lewis-writer.html |date=22 October 2012 }}, ''New Yorker,'' 5 May 2011. Retrieved 17 May 2011.</ref> [[Dick Van Dyke]] told a similar story. When he was just starting his career, he looked up Laurel's phone number, called him, and then visited him at his home. Van Dyke played Laurel on \"The Sam Pomerantz Scandals\" episode of ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]''.\n\nLaurel was offered a cameo role in ''[[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World]]'' (1963), but turned it down. He did not want to be on screen in his old age,<ref name=\"Karno\"/> especially without Hardy. The cameo appearance was then given to [[Jack Benny]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLaurel and [[Mae Dahlberg]] never married but lived together as common-law husband and wife from 1919 to 1925, before Dahlberg accepted a one-way ticket from [[Joe Rock]] to go back to her native Australia.<ref>Simon Louvish, ''Stan and Ollie, The Roots of Comedy'', Faber & Faber 2001 {{ISBN|0-571-21590-4}}</ref> In November 1937, Dahlberg was back in the US and sued Laurel for financial support. At the time, Laurel's second marriage was in the process of a divorce, with Dahlberg's legal suit adding to Laurel's woes. The matter was settled out of court.<ref>[https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19371207.1.4 ''San Bernardino Sun'', Volume 44, 7 December 1937, Page 4, \"Stan Laurels in Agreement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827165914/https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19371207.1.4 |date=27 August 2017 }} Accessed 15 April 2017.</ref> Dahlberg was described as a \"relief project worker\" by the court. Laurel was one of several popular British actors in Hollywood who never became naturalised US citizens.<ref>Prolgue: The Journal of the National Archives, p. 258. Washington, D.C., 1989</ref>\n\nLaurel had four wives and married one of them a second time after their divorce.<ref name=\"latimes.com\">Harnisch, Larry. [http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-then21-2009jun21,0,3596284.story?track=rss \"Stan Laurel's stormy marriage full of off-screen drama.\"] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', 21 June 2009. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> His first wife was [[Lois Neilson]], whom he married on 13 August 1926. Their daughter Lois was born on 10 December 1927 during the early years of Laurel and Hardy's partnership. In May 1930, their son Stanley was born two months premature and died after nine days. Laurel's daughter Lois died on 27 July 2017, aged 89.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lois-laurel-hawes-dead-stan-laurels-daughter-was-89-1025214 |title=Lois Laurel Hawes, Daughter of Stan Laurel, Dies at 89 |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809173457/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lois-laurel-hawes-dead-stan-laurels-daughter-was-89-1025214 |archive-date=9 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Laurel and Neilson divorced in December 1934.\n\nIn 1935, Laurel married Virginia Ruth Rogers (known as Ruth). In 1937, he filed for divorce, confessing that he was not over his ex-wife Lois, but Lois decided against a reconciliation. On New Year's Day 1938, Laurel married Vera Ivanova Shuvalova (known as Illeana), and Ruth accused him of bigamy, but their divorce had been finalised a couple of days before his new marriage. The new marriage was very volatile, and Illeana accused him of trying to bury her alive in the backyard of their San Fernando Valley home.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harnisch|first1=Larry|title=Stormy marriage full of off-screen drama for Stan Laurel|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/21/local/me-then21|accessdate=14 April 2018|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=21 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726193035/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/21/local/me-then21|archive-date=26 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He and Illeana separated in 1939 and divorced in 1940, with Illeana surrendering all claim to the Laurel surname on 1 February 1940 in exchange for $6,500.<ref>Associated Press, \"Surrenders Her Name\", ''The Spokesman-Review'', Spokane, Washington, Friday 2 February 1940, Volume 57, Number 264, page 2.</ref> In 1941, Laurel remarried Virginia Ruth Rogers; they were divorced for the second time in early 1946.<ref name=\"latimes.com\"/> On 6 May 1946, he married Ida Kitaeva Raphael to whom he remained married until his death.<ref name=\"latimes.com\"/>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Laurel grave.JPG|thumb|right|Stan Laurel's grave at Forest Lawn]]\nLaurel was a heavy smoker until suddenly quitting around 1960.<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1964-04.html \"Correspondence: April 4\u201329, 1964.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711221112/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1964-04.html |date=11 July 2018 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Project'' via ''lettersfromstan.com.'' Retrieved: 29 September 2018.</ref> In January 1965, he underwent a series of x-rays for an infection on the roof of his mouth.<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1965-01.html \"Correspondence: January 4\u201329, 1965.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903154327/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_1965-01.html |date=3 September 2011 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Project'' via ''lettersfromstan.com.'' Retrieved: 10 August 2011.</ref> He died on 23 February 1965, aged 74, four days after suffering a heart attack on 19 February.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1965/02/24/archives/stan-laurel-dies-i-movie-comedian-teamed-with-oliver-hardy-in-200.html \"Stan Laurel Dies. Teamed With Oliver Hardy in 200 Slapstick Films-Played 'Simple' Foil.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723214640/https://www.nytimes.com/1965/02/24/archives/stan-laurel-dies-i-movie-comedian-teamed-with-oliver-hardy-in-200.html |date=23 July 2018 }} ''The New York Times'', 24 February 1965. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> Minutes before his death, he told his nurse that he would not mind going skiing, and she replied that she was not aware that he was a skier. \"I'm not,\" said Laurel, \"I'd rather be doing that than this!\" A few minutes later he died quietly in his armchair.<ref>Bergen 1992, pp. 119\u2013120.</ref>\n\nAt his funeral, [[Buster Keaton]] said, \"[[Charlie Chaplin|Chaplin]] wasn't the funniest. I wasn't the funniest; this man was the funniest.\" [[Dick Van Dyke]] gave the eulogy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTw0TPv6n1s|title=Raw footage of Stan Laurels funeral with Dick Van Dyke, Buster Keaton and more|last=ebonyivorymovies|date=2 January 2014|via=YouTube|access-date=12 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609174226/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTw0TPv6n1s|archive-date=9 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> as a friend, prot\u00e9g\u00e9, and occasional impressionist of Laurel during his later years; he read \"[[The Clown's Prayer]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZRvfn1BCoHwC&pg=PT141&lpg=PT141&dq=Dick+Van+Dyke+a+prayer+for+clowns&source=bl&ots=f-0S_HsdgQ&sig=a3U2zAnu47IevPc7L1CqovPwM0M&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9_dDlrdbQAhUFwiYKHfEHB1sQ6AEIPzAG#v=onepage&q=Dick+Van+Dyke+a+prayer+for+clowns&f=false|title=My Lucky Life in and Out of Show Business: A Memoir|first=Dick Van|last=Dyke|date=3 May 2011|publisher=Crown/Archetype|via=Google Books}}</ref> Laurel had quipped, \"If anyone at my funeral has a long face, I'll never speak to him again.\"<ref name=\"Legacy\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=-h3-oAEoQMYC&pg=PA95 \"The Making of Stan Laurel: Echoes of a British Boyhood\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627191441/http://books.google.com/books?id=-h3-oAEoQMYC&pg=PA95 |date=27 June 2014 }}, p. 95. McFarland, 2011.</ref> He was interred in [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)|Forest Lawn\u2013Hollywood Hills Cemetery]].<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d ed.: 2 (Kindle Locations 26901-26907). McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers. Kindle Edition.</ref>\n\n==Legacy and honours==\n[[File:Statues of Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Statue of Stan Laurel and [[Oliver Hardy]] outside the Coronation Hall, [[Ulverston]], Cumbria, England]]\nLaurel and Hardy are featured on the cover of [[the Beatles]]' 1967 album ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]''.<ref>Levy 2005, p. 5.</ref> In 1989, a statue of Laurel was erected in Dockwray Square, [[North Shields]], [[Tyne and Wear]], England, where he lived at No. 8 from 1897 to 1902. The steps down from the Square to the North Shields Fish Quay were said to have inspired the piano-moving scene in ''[[The Music Box]]''. In a 2005 UK poll, ''Comedians' Comedian'', Laurel and Hardy were ranked top double act, and seventh overall.<ref name=\"Legacy\"/> Along with Hardy, Laurel was inducted into the [[Grand Order of Water Rats]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gowr.co.uk/roll-of-honour/ |title= Roll of Honour |publisher= Grand Order of Water Rats |accessdate= 17 April 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170418162039/http://www.gowr.co.uk/roll-of-honour/ |archive-date= 18 April 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n[[File:Stan Laurel Statue, Bishop Auckland.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Statue of Laurel on the site once occupied by the theatre owned by his parents, in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]], north east England]]\n[[Neil Brand]] wrote a radio play entitled ''[[Stan (play)|Stan]]'', broadcast in 2004 on [[BBC Radio 4]] and subsequently on [[BBC Radio 4 Extra]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0076mjl|title=Neil Brand - Stan - BBC Radio 4 Extra|website=BBC|access-date=25 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401162050/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0076mjl|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> starring [[Tom Courtenay]] as Stan Laurel, in which Stan visits Oliver Hardy after Hardy has suffered his stroke and tries to say the things to his dying friend and partner that have been left unsaid. In 2006, [[BBC Four]] showed a drama called ''Stan'', based on Brand's radio play, in which Laurel meets Hardy on his deathbed and reminisces about their career.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/cinema/features/silent-cinema-season.shtml \"BBC Four Cinema - Silent Cinema Season.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060624173712/http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/cinema/features/silent-cinema-season.shtml |date=24 June 2006 }} ''BBC''. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref>\n\nA plaque on the Bull Inn, [[Bottesford, Leicestershire]], England, marks Laurel and Hardy appearing in [[Nottingham]] over Christmas 1952, and staying with Laurel's sister, Olga, who was the landlady of the pub.<ref>[http://leicestershire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/the-battle-for-bottesford-the-border-town-of-nottinghamshire-and-leicestershire-23520/ \"The Battle for Bottesford \u2013 the border town of Nottinghamshire and Leicestershire.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207081335/http://leicestershire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/the-battle-for-bottesford-the-border-town-of-nottinghamshire-and-leicestershire-23520 |date=7 December 2010 }} ''Leicestershire Magazine'', 31 July 2010. Retrieved: 6 October 2010.</ref> In 2008, a statue of Stan Laurel was unveiled in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]], on the site of the Eden Theatre.<ref>Roberts, Will. [http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/3590723.Laurel_proves_Hardy_after_disaster_delays \"Laurel proves Hardy after disaster delays: Statue of Laurel arrives in Bishop Auckland.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005121533/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/3590723.Laurel_proves_Hardy_after_disaster_delays/ |date=5 October 2012 }} ''thenorthernecho'', 13 August 2008. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> In April 2009, a bronze statue of Laurel and Hardy was unveiled in Ulverston.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/8006614.stm \"Statue honours Laurel and Hardy.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420073138/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/8006614.stm |date=20 April 2009 }} ''BBC'', 19 April 2009. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/5183293/Hundreds-attend-Laurel-and-Hardy-statue-unveiling.html \"Hundreds attend Laurel and Hardy statue unveiling\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225221216/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/5183293/Hundreds-attend-Laurel-and-Hardy-statue-unveiling.html |date=25 December 2017 }}, ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved: 25 July 2012.</ref>\n\n[[File:Laurel and hardy autocorrect.JPG|thumb|upright|Laurel & Hardy Museum in Ulverston]]\nThere is a Laurel and Hardy Museum in Stan's hometown of Ulverston. There are two Laurel and Hardy museums in Hardy's hometown of [[Harlem, Georgia|Harlem]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. One is operated by the town of Harlem, and the other is a private museum owned and operated by Gary Russeth, a Harlem resident.\n\nIn 2013 [[Gail Louw]] and [[Jeffrey Holland (actor)|Jeffrey Holland]] debuted a short one-man play \"...And this is my friend Mr Laurel\" at the [[Camden Fringe]] festival. The play, starring Holland as Laurel, was taken on tour of the UK in 2014 until June 2015.<ref>[http://www.jeffreyholland.co.uk/Jeffrey_Holland/Mr_Laurel.html \"'...And this is my friend Mr Laurel'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306222553/http://www.jeffreyholland.co.uk/Jeffrey_Holland/Mr_Laurel.html |date=6 March 2015 }}, ''jeffreyholland.co.uk''. Retrieved: 2 March 2015.</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 film ''[[Stan & Ollie]]'', [[Steve Coogan]] portrayed Laurel (a performance which saw him nominated for the [[BAFTA Awards|BAFTA]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]]) and [[John C. Reilly]] played Hardy.<ref name=\"Stan & Ollie\">{{cite news|title=Steve Coogan and John C. Reilly will be Laurel and Hardy in Stan & Ollie|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/steve-coogan-john-c-reilly-will-laurel-hardy-stan-ollie/|publisher=Empire magazine|date=18 January 2016|access-date=19 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105173949/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/steve-coogan-john-c-reilly-will-laurel-hardy-stan-ollie/|archive-date=5 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Developed by [[BBC Films]], the film is set in the twilight of their careers, and focuses on their farewell tour of Britain and Ireland's [[variety show|variety]] halls in 1953.\n\n==Filmography==\n* [[Stan Laurel filmography]] (films of Stan Laurel as an actor without Oliver Hardy)\n* [[Laurel and Hardy filmography]] (filmography of Laurel and Hardy together)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|Biography|Comedy|Film}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=N}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* Bergen, Ronald. ''The Life and Times of Laurel and Hardy.'' New York: Smithmark, 1992. {{ISBN|0-8317-5459-1}}.\n* Bowers, Judith. ''Stan Laurel and Other Stars of the Panopticon: The Story of the Britannia Music Hall''. Edinburgh: Birlinn Ltd, 2007. {{ISBN|1-84158-617-X}}.\n* Louvish, Simon. ''Stan and Ollie: The Roots of Comedy''. London: Faber & Faber, 2001. {{ISBN|0-571-21590-4}}.\n* Marriot, A. J. ''Laurel & Hardy: The British Tours''. Hitchen, Herts, UK: AJ Marriot, 1993. {{ISBN|0-9521308-0-7}}.\n* Levy, Joe, ed. ''Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time''. New York: Wenner Books, 2005. {{ISBN|978-1-932958-61-4}}.\n* [[John McCabe (writer)|McCabe, John]]. ''Babe: The Life of Oliver Hardy''. London: Robson Books Ltd., 2004. {{ISBN|1-86105-781-4}}.\n* McCabe, John. ''Comedy World of Stan Laurel''. London: Robson Books, 2005, First edition 1975. {{ISBN|978-1-86105-780-8}}.\n* McCabe, John. ''Mr. Laurel & Mr. Hardy: An Affectionate Biography.'' London: Robson Books, 2004, First edition 1961, {{ISBN|1-86105-606-0}}.\n* Stone, Rob. ''Laurel or Hardy: The Solo Films of Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy.'' Temecula, California: Split Reel Books, 1996\n* Okuda, Ted, and James L. Neibaur. ''Stan Without Ollie: The Stan Laurel Solo Films.'' Jefferson, NC: McFarland and Co., 2012\n* Guiles, Fred Lawrence. ''Stan: The Life of Stan Laurel''. New York: Stein and Day., 1980\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Stan Laurel |sopt=t}}\n* {{IMDb name|0491048}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=109430|name=Stan Laurel}}\n* ''[http://www.brentonfilm.com/articles/the-making-of-stan-laurel-echoes-of-a-british-boyhood The Making of Stan Laurel: Echoes of a British Boyhood]'' article at [http://www.brentonfilm.com/ Brenton Film] by Danny Lawrence, Stan Laurel's biographer\n* [http://www.laurel-and-hardy-museum.co.uk/ Laurel and Hardy Museum, Ulverston]\n* [http://www.lettersfromstan.com/ The Stan Laurel Correspondence Archive Project]\n\n{{Laurel and Hardy}}\n{{Academy Honorary Award}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward LifeAchievement 1960\u20131979}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laurel, Stan}}\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:Laurel and Hardy|*]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Lancashire]]\n[[Category:British male comedy actors]]\n[[Category:English entertainers]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male silent film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English stunt performers]]\n[[Category:Grand Order of Water Rats members]]\n[[Category:Music hall performers]]\n[[Category:Silent film comedians]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Academy Honorary Award recipients]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:Hal Roach Studios actors]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer contract players]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:British expatriate male actors in the United States]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Tynemouth]]\n[[Category:People educated at Stonelaw High School]]\n[[Category:People from Ulverston]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:19th-century English people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English comedians]]\n", "name_user": "Diopic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:addCategory:Screen Actors Guild Life Achievement Award", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stan_Laurel"}
{"title_page": "Rhythm Nation (music video)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rhythm Nation\n| starring       = [[Janet Jackson]]\n| director       = [[Dominic Sena]]\n| producer       = \n| studio         = [[A&M Records]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1989|09|19|mf=y}} <small>(premiere)</small>\n| runtime        = {{Duration|m=4|s=27}}\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| music          = Janet Jackson, [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n}}\n\nThe '''music video''' for recording artist [[Janet Jackson]]'s single '''\"[[Rhythm Nation]]\"''' was directed by [[Dominic Sena]]. It was filmed as part of the long-form video ''Rhythm Nation 1814 Film'' at a power plant located in [[Pasadena, California]]. The video is notable for its \"post-apocalyptic\" warehouse setting, the unisex black military-style uniforms in which Jackson and her dancers were outfitted, and its choreography, considered to \"set the template for hundreds of videos to come in the Nineties and aughts.\"\n\nThe video's outfit has received various tributes, being displayed at [[Walt Disney World]] theme park, [[Rock & Roll Hall of Fame]]'s \"Women Who Rock: Vision, Passion, Power\" exhibit, and the [[National Museum of Women in the Arts]]. A wax figure of Jackson wearing the outfit was also included in [[Madame Tussaud]]'s exhibits in [[Hollywood]] and [[New York City]], as well as Tussaud's [[Rock Circus]] exhibit in [[London]]. The song and choreography is also a mainstay at [[talent shows]] worldwide, and has been performed at ''[[The X Factor]]'', ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'', and ''[[America's Best Dance Crew]]'', with an [[Australia]]n music show also named after the song. Various actors and choreographers, including [[Wade Robson]] and [[Travis Payne]], have cited Jackson and the \"Rhythm Nation\" routine as a primary influence to their careers.\n\nIt won multiple accolades, including [[MTV]]'s [[Video Vanguard Award]] for Jackson's impact on entertainment. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' considered the video \"legendary,\" and ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' included it in a list of 10 Favorite Dancing Musicians, calling Jackson \"a brilliant dancer\" whom it said had \"arguably had a greater long-term impact on the choreography of contemporary music videos\" even than her own brother [[Michael Jackson]] had had.<ref name=entweekly/> The publication also titled it \"the gold standard for [[dystopia]]n dance pop music videos,\" featuring \"some of the most memorable choreography in pop video history.\"<ref name=bestapocalyptic/> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' considered Janet's choreography to be \"even more enthralling\" than those of her contemporaries.<ref name=latimes>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-04-15/entertainment/ca-1888_1_janet-jackson/4|title=Janet Jackson Finally Learns to Say 'I'|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Hilburn, Robert|date=2015-04-90|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[black-and-white]], military-inspired \"Rhythm Nation\" video was directed by [[Dominic Sena]] in August 1989. It was the finale in the ''Rhythm Nation 1814 Film,'' following videos for \"[[Miss You Much]]\" and \"The Knowledge\", respectively. Known for its high-octane choreography in an abandoned factory, the video won an award for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]] and was nominated for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Dance Video|Best Dance Video]] at the [[MTV Video Music Awards]], where Jackson also received the [[MTV Video Vanguard Award]].<ref>{{citation|title=MTV Video Music Awards nominees|newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|date=20 September 5, 1990|page=5}}</ref><ref name=\"MTVMVA\">{{citation|author=Francesca Chapman|title=Sinead Takes MTV's Top Video Award|newspaper=[[Philadelphia Daily News]]|date=20 September 7, 1990|page=65}}</ref> \"Rhythm Nation\" ranked at thirty-seven on [[VH1]]'s \"Greatest 100 Videos\" and forty-four on [[MTV]]'s \"100 Greatest Videos Ever Made\". The video features a young [[Tyrin Turner]]. The success of \"Rhythm Nation\" allowed Sena to direct such subsequent films as ''[[Swordfish (film)|Swordfish]],'' ''[[Gone in 60 Seconds (2000 film)|Gone in 60 Seconds]],'' and ''[[Season of the Witch (2011 film)|Season of the Witch]].''\n\n==Development==\nThe \"Rhythm Nation\" video was filmed simultaneously with \"[[Miss You Much]]\" and \"The Knowledge,\" which were later combined to form the long-form music video ''Rhythm Nation 1814 Film.'' The video was filmed over a period of twenty days at the Pasadena Power Plant in [[Pasadena, California]], and served as the finale in the series.\n\nSpeaking to MTV, Jackson said, \"I knew who I wanted to direct \u2019Rhythm Nation,\u2019 that was simple: Dominic Sena. After working with him on \u2019[[Let's Wait Awhile]],\u2019 I absolutely fell in love with him. [...] Dominic understood story, and he could put onscreen, from front to back, the whole picture you had in your head.\" Deciphering the video's scenery, Jackson explained, \"the foggy, smoky street and the dark, black-and-white tone, that was all intentional. When you've done a lot of videos, it can be difficult to keep it fresh and new. You have to try something you've never done, in fear of looking like something you've already created.\"<ref name=video>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zrBolXPYq40C&pg=RA4-PT179|title=I Want My MTV: The Uncensored Story of the Music Video Revolution|publisher=Tannenbaum, Rob|page=179|date=October 11, 2027|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The video was shot in black-and-white to locate everybody's skin tone within shades of grey, portraying the ''Rhythm Nation'''s slogan: ''\"We are like-minded individuals, sharing a common vision, pushing toward a world rif of color-lines.\"''<ref>The Face Magazine, 1990. Page 77</ref> \"There were so many races in that video, from Black to White and all the shades of gray in between. [[Black-and-white photography]] shows all those shades, and that's why we used it,\" said Jackson.<ref name=ebony>[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]'', February 1990. Page 50</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Janet Jackson Rhythm Nation.jpg|thumb|Jackson (center) performing in the music video for \"Rhythm Nation\" surrounded by male and female dancers, all outfitted in unisex black military-style uniforms.]] -->\n\"We're living in a very visual time right now,\" Jackson explains. \"That's why videos are so important. Before, they really weren't. They play such an important part in the music business. The next is the live show. But the first they ever see of you is the video.\"<ref>[[British Vogue]], 1990. Page 578</ref> Describing Jackson on the set of the video, journalist [[David Ritz]] said \"Janet Jackson's mood seems retiring, but underneath, like so much else about her, there's more than meets the eye. For hours she obliges the camera during a grueling photography session on a sun-soaked day at the [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] Power Plant, a central locale for her black-and-white-dance video, a mysterious and metaphorical work dramatizing the concerns of ''Rhythm Nation.\"'' Jackson's clothes were considered to reflect \"a quiet sadness,\" being \"cooperative to a fault, yet inwardly shy.\"<ref name=essence>Essence Magazine, March 1990. Page 54</ref>\n\nJackson was often questioned for her black attire and uniforms, saying \"A lady came up to me and asked, 'Why do you always wear so much black? Is it because it is slimming?'\"<ref name=ebony/> \"Wearing black shows that for once that you can represent something positive and not negative,\" she emphasized, and offered harsh words for those who equate negativity with the color black, referring to the day the [[stock market]] crashed being known as \"[[Black Monday (1987)|Black Monday]]\". Jackson responds. Jackson recalled being hurt over the comments of an [[African-American]] critic who considered her black attire \"drab,\" saying \"He's been brainwashed because he can't see what I'm trying to show - and that hurt me so bad. I would hope that everyone will understand that for once black represents something good.\"<ref name=ebony/> \"That's why I decided the color scheme for ''Rhythm Nation'' - the costumes, the cover art, the overall feeling - would be positively, uncompromisingly Black.\"<ref name=essence/> Several label executives reportedly told Jackson the album and video wouldn't have \"crossover\" appeal. With Jackson's persistence, the video became \"the most far-reaching single project the company has ever attempted.\"<ref name=ebony/> In a later interview, Jackson said \"The concept basically was very industrial [[black and white]], not wanting any color brought to it\" - \"no color lines is was it was, so everyone is all somewhat of the same kind of tone.\" \"Dominic Sena directed it, it was a twenty day shoot. A lot of work, long hours.\"<ref>http://www.mtv.com/videos/misc/213453/on-the-rhythm-nation-video.jhtml On 'The 'Rhythm Nation' Video'</ref> Sena commented \"She's always out there trying to give people something different and fresh, and exciting to look at. If it's been done before she doesn't want anything to do with it, it's like 'let's start over'. Part of the reason she gravitated toward a new choreographer this time, a young guy who hadn't had that much experience, an amazing street dancer, and they developed a rapport and she said 'nobody's seen this guy's stuff before, I'll work with him. We'll develop these steps and give people something fresh to look at.\"<ref>Making of \"Rhythm Nation\", Rhythm Nation 1814 Film release</ref>\n\n==Choreography==\nThe video's choreography has been considered one of the most recognizable and imitated routines in pop culture. Co-choreographer Anthony Thomas said, \"she's not a trained dancer/ It comes from her soul. She's a natural. She's unbelievable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-03-02/entertainment/ca-1920_1_jackson-dances|title=Jackson Dances--'It Comes From Her Soul' |work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Wine, Steven|date=2002-03-90|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' included the video in a list of \"10 Favorite Dancing Musicians\", calling Jackson \"a brilliant dancer\" who has \"arguably had a greater long-term impact on the choreography of contemporary music videos\" than [[Michael Jackson]], setting a format for \"hundreds\" of subsequent videos.<ref name=rollingstone>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/rolling-stone-readers-pick-their-10-favorite-dancing-musicians-20110714/8-janet-jackson-0596086|title=Rolling Stone Readers Pick Their 10 Favorite Dancing Musicians|work=Rolling Stone|date=July 11, 2014|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The publication said \"Jackson leads what appears to be a hip paramilitary organization through some of the most memorable choreography in pop video history.\"<ref name=bestapocalyptic/> The publication also exclaimed Jackson's \"dazzling dancing\" and the \"can-humans-really-do-that? choreography\" in the video \"is on a par with, and may even top, the best of brother Michael's hoof-happy videos\", commending her \"lightning speed\".<ref name=telemusical/>\n\n''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' commented \"Ms. Jackson and her crew put on their military jackets and did the finely choreographed routine that fans everywhere wore out countless [[VHS]] tapes rewinding to memorize.\"<ref name=poll>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/468693/the-10-best-80s-music-videos-poll-results|title=The 10 Best '80s Music Videos: Poll Results|work=Billboard|publisher=Letkemann, Jessica|date=August 11, 2011|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> ''Sweat, Tears, and Jazz Hands'' author Mike Weaver commended the video's impact on choreography, declaring \"praised for its probing lyrics and video and production innovation, made her recognized and respected dancer and performer in the industry. Janet Jackson and her crew's innovative, one-of-a-kind, funk-and-groove choreography was unlike anything seen in the history of pop music. [...] By the early '90s, every show choir and every [[Hip hop music|hiphop]] dancer wanted to cut and paste parts and pieces of the Rhythm Nation production into their set.\"<ref name=weaver>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nfAyaqJ7JSsC&pg=PT171|title=Sweat, Tears, and Jazz Hands: The Official History of Show Choir from Vaudeville to Glee|publisher=Weaver, Mike|year=2011|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The book ''Gender and Qualitative Methods'' suggested the routine represents \"self-control and military discipline\" - \"they move in unison and in the same rhythm, dancing like roots, with stiff square arm movements,\" also exhibiting [[Asia]]n martial arts.<ref name=gender/> ''[[The Orlando Sentinel]]'' regarded Jackson to portray \"Swiss-watch precision\" in the routine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1990-04-28/lifestyle/9004276096_1_milli-vanilli-lip-synced-vocals|title=Pop Concert Or Mime Show?|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=2028-04-90|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> [[Slant Magazine]] said the clip \"anointed Janet the ambassador of intricately choreographed,\" being among \"the most intricately and powerfully choreographed music videos of all time.\"<ref name=greatestvideos/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/janet-jackson-damita-jo|title=Janet Jackson: Damita Jo - Music Review |work=Slant Magazine|publisher=Cinquemani, Sal|date=March 4, 2023|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' said the routine was \"made famous by its memorably routine- infested video,\" described as \"an aerobic goose step\" by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/jul/28/artsfeatures|title=Pop review: Janet Jackson |work=The Guardian|publisher=Clarke, Betty|date=July 1, 2027|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=battle/>  [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]] ranked the video as having the \"Best Dance Moves in a Music Video\" in 2013, commenting \"the dance moves \u2014 from the finger count down to the standing split \u2014 were as crisp as the uniforms.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bet.com/music/photos/2013/09/werk-best-dance-moves-in-a-music-video.html#!090513-music-dance-moves-janet-jackson-rythm-nation|title=Werk: Best Dance Moves in a Music Video - Music |work=BET|date=2009\u201313|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> [[Geico]] also noted [[The Running Man (dance)|The Running Man]] dance gained fame through the video.<ref name=\"Geico\">{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/geico/the-happiest-dance-crazes-throughout-time|title=The Happiest Dance Crazes Throughout Time|work=Buzzfeed|publisher=[[Geico]]|date=March 13, 2006|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAnother critique stated \"most of the video consists of Jackson with background dancers performing a synchronized dance routine. Judging by the serious facial expressions and vigorous body movements of Jackson and her dancers, the men and women in \u201cRhythm Nation\u201d are confident, courageous, and display unmatched conviction.\"<ref name=crossroads/> Jackson and her dancers were analyzed to \"march toward the camera in a dominating manner\" while simultaneously \"performing moves that most humans couldn\u2019t accomplish without a personal trainer and lots of free time on their hands.\"<ref name=lageose>{{cite web|url=http://lageose9.blogspot.com/2013/05/janet-jackson-rhythm-nation.html|title=Backup Dancers From Hell: Janet Jackson \u2013 \"Rhythm Nation\"|work=Blogspot|publisher=Lageose, Brian|date=May 13, 2027|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> A brief scene potentially depicting sexuality in the video's choreography was also debated, though the video was ultimately praised for its depiction of social themes, explaining \"Although there are no sexually explicit lyrics or messages in \u201cRhythm Nation\u201d that would be obvious to audiences, there is a short scene two minutes and thirty eight seconds into the music video that is somewhat sexual. [...] Instead of using sexual elements to attract audiences, it portrays the strong bond between entertainers and social activists with a common goal.\"<ref name=crossroads/>\n\n==Outfit==\nThe outfit worn for the video and performances of the song is infamous in popular culture. Jackson's appearance includes \"a fearless red-lipped pout and long black [[ponytail]],\" along with \"a black baseball hat with a metal \"1814\" applique, a black military-style shirt jacket with silver buckles and faux leather straps and collar, black belted pants and chunky, strappy boots.\"<ref name=sb>{{cite web|url=http://www.soulbounce.com/soul/2010/12/16_janet_jackson_barbie_dolls_that_wed_like_to_see.php|title=16 Janet Jackson Barbie Dolls That We'd Like To See|work=SoulBounce|date=December 10, 2009|accessdate=January 4, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203070244/http://www.soulbounce.com/soul/2010/12/16_janet_jackson_barbie_dolls_that_wed_like_to_see.php|archivedate=December 3, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Another analysis observed Jackson and her dancers \"dressed in black, cadet-style costumes that cover the entire body except the face.\"<ref name=crossroads/> A biography of Jackson stated she attempted her performances to \"center around her and her dancers, who would act as \"soldiers\" in a kind of army of reformers. Her outfit was a dark, buttonedup uniform, and she moved in tight formation with her dancers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bp5bAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT46|title=\nJanet Jackson - Cindy Dyson - Google Books|work=Infobase Learning|publisher=Dyson, Cindy|year=2000|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' also said the clip \"stars Ms. Jackson buttoned up tight in a tailored uniform, with an Army issue coat, epaulets and combat boots.\"<ref name=battle>{{cite web|url=http://www2.nytimes.com/1990/04/22/arts/tv-view-have-women-surrendered-in-mtv-s-battle-of-the-sexes.html?pagewanted=4&src=pm|title=TV VIEW; Have Women Surrendered In MTV's Battle of the Sexes? - Page 4 |work=The New York Times|publisher=Texier, Katherine|date=October 11, 2014|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> An additional anecdote from the publication noted \"Ms. Jackson, done up in black military-inspired garb, was eager to rail against societal ills like racism and domestic abuse.\"<ref name=tempest>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/04/arts/capitalizing-on-jackson-tempest.html?pagewanted=2|title=Capitalizing On Jackson Tempest - Page 2 |work=The New York Times|publisher=Ogunnaike, Lola|date=February 4, 2004|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Janet jackson.png|thumb|Jackson performing \"Rhythm Nation\" on the [[Number Ones, Up Close and Personal]] tour, 2011.]]\nChris Ryan of [[MTV]] praised Jackson's look as trendsetting, saying \"Janet took her place at the top of the trendsetting heap.\" MTV's Rebecca Thomas also commented Jackson \"made a signature of dangling-key earrings, boxy black hats and suits adorned in gold hardware\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/04/02/janet-jacksons-look-the-good-the-bad-and-the-wtf/|title=Janet Jackson\u2019s Look: The Good, The Bad And The WTF!?|publisher=MTV|date=April 10, 2002|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1706906/rihanna-777-tour-television-special.jhtml|title=Rihanna Brings '777,' '90s Flashbacks And Dancehall To Brooklyn|publisher=MTV|date=May 13, 2008|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Julianne Escobedo Shepherd of [[MTV News|MTV Style]] spoke about its influence, recalling that \"everyone wanted to dress like her\" and dance classes would \"dedicate hours\" to the video's choreography; \"she had her own personal Rhythm Nation hardware and bondage straps; I can't figure out or remember if she predated the Boy London hardware caps, but both were around the same time, and she was influential enough that it's not unlikely her steez gave them the idea.\"<ref name=style>{{cite web|url=http://style.mtv.com/2013/05/16/janet-jackson-style-icon/|title=Style Icon: Janet Jackson - MTV Style|publisher=MTV News|date=May 13, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>  An additional critique regarded the video's wardrobe \"intimidating\" and \"uniform fetish,\" likened to \"some type of dark-ops cadet corps.\"<ref name=lageose/> Other aspects of Jackson's ensemble in the clip are also regarded as influential. ''[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]'' also praised Jackson as a trendsetter, commenting \"she started her own movement with the hoop earrings with the solo key.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://photos.essence.com/galleries/essence-icon-janet-jackson?slide=24140|title=ESSENCE Icon: Janet Jackson|work=Essenceaccessdate=04-01-14}}</ref> Retail outlet [[Karmaloop]] called Jackson's snapback hat \"80s signature style\", selling a hat based on Jackson's.<ref name=karma>{{cite web|url=http://www.karmaloop.com/product/The-Rhythm-Nation-Leather-Snapback/385818|title=This Is A Love Song Hat Rhythm Nation Snapback |work=Karmaloop|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> MTV credited the hat worn in the video as one of the reasons for the snapback hat's revival in popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://style.mtv.com/2013/01/15/rihanna-ciara-leather-snapback/|title=Get A Leather Snapback Like Rihanna, Kat Graham, Ciara And Brandy|publisher=MTV|date=January 13, 2015|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' included the outfit at number nineteen on a list of 50 Stars Who Rocked Fashion, commenting Jackson adopted a \"crisp military look for the ladies \u2014 with epaulets, cadet caps, fierce tailoring.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20309550_20536569_21066616,00.html|title=\nJanet Jackson - 50 Stars Who Rocked Fashion: Top 25 |work=Entertainment Weekly|date=October 11, 2014|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Lucky (magazine)|Lucky Magazine]]'' ranked the video among \"The 18 Most Stylishly Influential Music Videos of All Time\".<ref name=lucky>{{cite web|url=http://www.luckymag.com/style/2013/11/most-stylish-music-videos_slideshow_item15_16|title=Janet Jackson, \"Rhythm Nation\" - The 18 Most Stylishly Influential Music Videos Of All Time|work=Lucky Magazine|date=2011\u201313|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The same year, ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' listed \"Rhythm Nation\" among the \"10 Most Iconic Music Video Looks of the 80s\".<ref name=cosmopolitan>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/news/all-hail-acid-wash-denim|title=10 Most Iconic Music Video Looks of The 80s |work=Cosmopolitan|publisher=Manning, Charles|date=November 13, 2006|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, Alexander Fury of ''[[The Independent]]'' called Jackson a \"style icon\", exclaiming \"the artwork created with Eighties illustrator [[Tony Viramontes]] for ''[[Control (Janet Jackson album)|Control]]'' stands the test of time, as does the video for 1989's \"Rhythm Nation\", adding he was \"obsessed\" with the video's \"get-up of quasi-military uniform accessorised with a single key on a hoop earring.\" Fury also said Jackson \"deserves a place in the fashion hall of fame\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/fashion/features/alexander-fury-ive-long-been-obsessed-with-rhythm-nation-8538095.html|title=Alexander Fury: I've long been obsessed with Rhythm Nation - Features - Fashion|work=The Independent|publisher=Fury, Alexander|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nThe themes of unity among the dancers and various ethnicities, as well as gender equality, has received praise from critics.\n\n[[Slant Magazine]] observed \"The solidarity of Janet Jackson's multi-racial Rhythm Nation dancers is evoked with hyper-synchronized movements while their individuality is expressed via their separate, distinct dances.\"<ref name=greatestvideos/> ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised Jackson as a feminist, proclaiming \"although most female characters on [[MTV]] are still reclining, swept off their feet by the fantasies of self-serving musicians and video directors, more singers are getting up and standing on their own two feet. You only have to catch Janet Jackson's hit, ''Rhythm Nation'' to be convinced that a change has taken place,\" calling it \"a far cry from the lascivious bodies in various states of undress that flood the channel.\"<ref name=battle/> ''[[34th Street Magazine]]'' applauded the video's implication of gender neutrality, saying \"\u201cRhythm Nation\u201d makes a far superior statement on the fluidity of gender. In this video, men and women dress and dance identically and no one\u2019s really sexualized. Everyone just knows how to move. In other words, sometimes the best way to send a positive message is not to try so damn hard.\"<ref name=partofme/> The clip's theme of activism and leadership was also commended, writing \"instead of using sexual elements to attract audiences, it portrays the strong bond between entertainers and social activists with a common goal,\" in an attempt to speaks \"particularly to young people and encourages them to be the leaders of tomorrow. Jackson passes on the message of social activist Mahatma Gandhi who once said, \u201cYou must be the change you wish to see in the world.\"<ref name=crossroads/> A biography stated the video spreads \"a message of love that was neither naive not superficial.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G132LEhM4ucC&pg=PA61|title=Michael Jackson, the Man Behind the Mask: An Insider's Story of the King of Pop|publisher=Jones, Bob|year=2005|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe video features dancers of \"[[African-American]], [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]], and [[Asia]]n ancestry,\" aiding Jackson in becoming known for \"breaking existing racial stereotypes specifically toward African-American women,\" depicting her as a \"socially responsible citizen with dignity and grace.\"<ref name=crossroads/> The backing dancers in the video were thought to represent \"[[Activism|social activists]]\", shrouded by \"empty surroundings\" deciphered as \"the indifferent attitudes in society.\" Jackson and her dancers were considered \"confident, courageous,\" and displaying \"unmatched conviction\". The video was used as an example of \"positive gender performance of black women in a music video\" in the book ''Gender and Qualitative Methods'', considered to produce \"a new kind of desire and a new position for a female viewer (and listener).\" The video's director was noted to construct Jackson as \"a creative, intelligent professional, someone who aims at promoting the status of black people, especially women.\"\nDressed in identical uniforms, Jackson and the dancers \"move in unison and in the same rhythm, dancing like roots, with stiff square arm movements. ... Jackson is also dressed in a uniform and is performing asexually and almost anonymously in front of, but as one of the members of the group.\"<ref name=gender>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7f7nFXfmPBMC&pg=PA92|title=Gender and Qualitative Methods|publisher=J\u00e4rviluoma, Helmi|date=October 3, 2021|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The video was also one of the only popular music videos considered suitable to be broadcast to [[US troops]] in [[Middle Eastern]] countries such as [[Saudi Arabia]] and the [[Persian Gulf]] due to religious restrictions on the portrayal of female sexuality. Commenting on the situation, VH1 executive Jackie Sharp said \"It's the perfect women's video, because they're all buttoned up to the neck and nobody touches\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,313333,00.html|title=Middle East Cover-Up |work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Harris, Mark|date=2015-02-91|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Long-form music video==\nThe full-length music video, known as the ''Rhythm Nation 1814 Film'', consists of the videos for \"[[Miss You Much]]\", \"The Knowledge\", and \"Rhythm Nation\", filmed simultaneously over a period of twenty days. It received a [[Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video]]. The video premiered in full on September 16, 1989 on MTV to high ratings, and was aired several times the following week.<ref name=telemusical>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-09-16/entertainment/ca-285_1_fancy-footwork|title=TV Reviews : Fancy Footwork Rescues Pretentious Jackson Show |work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Willman, Chris|date=2016-09-89|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Producer [[Jimmy Jam]] said \"The concept for the half-hour, long-form video was already in the works when we recorded the album. Janet's [[choreographer]] was here, so we knew what the steps were going to be for the songs, how the story would be treated, and how the video was going to look. [...] We actually tried to make the album sound a little like the black-and-white images in the video, rather than adapting the video to the album. A lot of the music was treated almost as [[soundtrack]].\"<ref>''[[Keyboard (magazine)|Keyboard]]'', May 1990. Pages 26-27</ref> While filming \"The Knowledge\", Jackson collapsed from exhaustion after filming for over 25 consecutive hours, explaining \"That's the one area where I must be careful. Sometimes I won't sleep, won't stop reviewing, won't stop searching for ways to improve the projects. The projects absorb me. When we were filming the long video, I actually collapsed.\"<ref name=ritz>Essence Magazine, March 1990. Page 116</ref> Describing the situation, journalist [[David Ritz]], who attended the video's filming, commented \"Looking at \"The Knowledge,\" it appears that Janet's physical breakdown came at the emotional climax of the video. \"[[Prejudice]], no!\" she cries, kicking and smashing windows with the anger of a soul possessed. \"[[Ignorance]], no! [[Bigotry]], no! [[Illiteracy]], no!\" she bemoans, before falling onto the ledge of the roof, dangerously positioned on the edge, ominous clouds of change racing overhead.\"<ref name=ritz/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe \"Rhythm Nation\" video received favorable reviews from critics and journalists, focusing on its theme of unity and choreography. Comparing [[Lady Gaga]] to Jackson, Kyle Anderson of [[MTV News]] described it as \"the clip that sent Jackson into the stratosphere as an envelope-pushing pop star.\"<ref name=ryan>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.mtv.com/2010/06/02/lady-gaga-alejandro-video-preview/|title=\u2018Alejandro\u2019 Video Preview: Lady Gaga Tips Her Hat To Madonna And Janet Jackson|publisher=MTV|date=June 10, 2002|accessdate=January 4, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140108233429/http://newsroom.mtv.com/2010/06/02/lady-gaga-alejandro-video-preview/|archivedate=January 8, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote =\n\"Shot in stark black and white and set in a smokey, oppressive factory setting, Jackson leads what appears to be a hip paramilitary organization through some of the most memorable choreography in pop video history. The future may look bleak, but at least it's funky.\" \u2014 [[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]<ref name=bestapocalyptic/>\n\n\"Janet's dance nation is a hard, angular, geometric battle plan, and as the title track's stunning, monochromatic video clip confirms, the schematic first calls for an almost [[Zen]]-like transcendence of self.\" \u2014 [[Slant Magazine]]<ref name=slant>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/best-singles-of-the-1980s/P4|title=The 100 Best Singles of the 1980s - Feature |work=Slant Magazine|date=August 12, 2020|accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n| width  = 30em\n| align  = right\n| quoted = 1\n}}\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called the video \"legendary,\" and ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' included it in a list of \"10 Favorite Dancing Musicians,\" calling Jackson \"a brilliant dancer\" who has \"arguably had a greater long-term impact on the choreography of contemporary music videos\" than [[Michael Jackson]]. The publication added the video \"set the template for hundreds of videos to come in the Nineties and aughts.\"<ref name=entweekly>{{cite web|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/glee-season-5-episode-7-puppet-master/2/|title='Glee' recap: No Strings Attached|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=November 13, 2029|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=rollingstone/> It was also included in a list of the \"Ten Best [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|Apocalyptic]] Dance Music Videos\" in 2011, heralded as \"the gold standard for [[dystopia]]n [[Dance-pop|dance pop]] music videos\" which features \"some of the most memorable choreography in pop video history.\"<ref name=bestapocalyptic>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/ten-best-apocalyptic-dance-music-videos-20110406/janet-jackson-rhythm-nation-1989-0545021|title=Ten Best Apocalyptic Dance Music Videos|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=04-06-11}}</ref> ''[[The Sun Sentinel]]'' called it \"dark, futuristic,\" and \"unforgettable,\" adding \"No one can witness the militaristic precision of Rhythm Nation, which gives the impression that a really angry pep squad has taken over the dance floor, and not see how Janet's style has been sampled, borrowed and stolen over and over ... and over.\"<ref name=sun>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2001-03-18/entertainment/0103160621_1_mtv-icon-janet-jackson-pop-culture|title=Welcome To Planet Janet: It's Our World|work=The Sun Sentinel|publisher=Winston, Sherri|date=March 1, 2018|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' listed it among the \"10 Most Iconic Music Video Looks of the 80s\", saying \"How do you step out from behind the shadow of the world\u2019s biggest pop star? You strap on some black, wear a key as an earring and dance like you\u2019re going to war. Janet is a style General and all the rest better fall in line.\"<ref name=cosmopolitan/> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' ranked the video among the \"100 Greatest Music Videos\", calling the \"stunning, monochromatic\" video it \"one of the most intricately and powerfully choreographed music videos of all time,\" saying \"the solidarity of Janet Jackson's multi-racial Rhythm Nation dancers is evoked with hyper-synchronized movements while their individuality is expressed via their separate, distinct dances.\"<ref name=greatestvideos>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/100-greatest-music-videos/P2|title=100 Greatest Music Videos - Feature |work=Slant Magazine|publisher=Gonzalez, Ed|date=June 3, 2029|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The publication observed Jackson \"saw dance as a movement in both senses of the word: an athletic extension of ones own socio-political force of will,\" as well as a \"obliterator of races, genders, creeds,\" calling for a \"[[Zen]]-like transcendence of self.\"<ref name=slantreview>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/janet-jackson-janet-jacksons-rhythm-nation-1814/1826|title=Janet Jackson: Janet Jackson's Rhythm Nation 1814 - Music Review |work=Slant Magazine|publisher=Henderson, Eric|date=September 9, 2006|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The publication also stated, \"if the song's music video inadvertently recalled the spirit of [[Leni Riefenstahl]], its vision of unity through mandatory multiculturalism reverses the [[Nazi]] demagogue's ideology.\"<ref name=greatestdance>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/100-greatest-dance-songs/P8|title=100 Greatest Dance Songs - Feature |work=Slant Magazine|date=January 6, 2030|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Additional commentary said the clip \"wasn\u2019t the norm for most things in the 80s, let alone a pop music video.\"<ref name=afropunk>{{cite web|url=http://www.afropunk.com/profiles/blogs/are-you-a-part-of-the-rhythm-nation|title=Are You A Part of the Rhythm Nation|publisher=Afro-punk.com|date=March 13, 2007|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Another review considered it \"groundbreaking\" and \"famous for its dynamic choreography in an abandoned factory,\" exclaiming \"Fast-paced and bold, viewers become hooked to the catchy tunes and soulful sounds of the groundbreaking dance video.\"<ref name=crossroads>{{cite web|url=http://christophertorrenueva.wordpress.com/tag/rhythm-nation/|title=Rhythm Nation - CROSSING CROSSROADS|work=Wordpress|publisher=Torrenueva, Christopher|date=February 10, 2013|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[PopEater]]'' commented \"Known for her scene-setting, story-telling videos, her call to action video for 'Rhythm Nation' is no exception\", adding Jackson's \"military-styled high kicks and dance sequences take the cake.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popeater.com/hot-topics/janet-jackson-music-videos/|title=Janet Jackson's Iconic Music Videos|work=PopEater|publisher=Glinow, Kiki Von|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' considered it \"groundbreaking,\" also \"striking, timeless and instantly recognizable.\"<ref name=bet>{{cite web|url=http://www.bet.com/music/photos/2012/05/the-evolution-of-janet-jackson.html#!051512-music-evolution-janet-jackson-rhythm-nation-album|title=The Evolution of Janet Jackson - Music - BET|date=2005\u201312|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20396305_84846,00.html|title=Action Jacksons - Michael Jackson Remembered |work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Seymour, Craig|date=2007-12-99|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Elena Gooray of ''[[34th Street Magazine]]'' praised the video's overall theme, concept, and wardrobe, exclaiming \"Janet\u2019s messages? Justice, togetherness, the power of dance. Those ideas are simple and almost by definition inoffensive. Her use of military themes? Only to inspire her wardrobe and some incredibly synchronized dance routines with bangin\u2019 choreography.\"<ref name=partofme>{{cite web|url=http://34st.com/2012/04/part-of-me/|title=We want no part of 'Part of Me' |work=34th Street Magazine|publisher=Gooray, Elena|date=April 12, 2006|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\nMusic journalist [[Richard Croft (tenor)|Richard Croft]] considered it \"captivating, saying \"Anyone with an interest in music videos, dancing, military jackets or nunchucks \u2013 you need to see the short film that accompanied \u2018Rhythm Nation\u2019. It is incredible, one of the top five music videos ever made.\" Croft added, \"I\u2019ve never seen dancing like that in a video, and no matter how many times I see it, I can never look away. It\u2019s captivating. \u2018Rhythm Nation\u2019 is the most empowering, come-on-get-up song in the world. They should play it before sporting matches like the national anthem. Yet the lyrics never say that thinking positively and coming together is all we need to do to achieve our goals \u2013 there was work to do in 1989, there\u2019s work to do now. No struggle, no progress.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thegospelaccordingtorichardcroft.wordpress.com/2010/06/01/20-janet-jackson-rhythm-nation-1989/|title=20. Janet Jackson \u2013 \u2018Rhythm Nation\u2019 (1989)|work=Wordpress|publisher=Croft, Richard|date=June 10, 2001|accessdate=January 4, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109000519/http://thegospelaccordingtorichardcroft.wordpress.com/2010/06/01/20-janet-jackson-rhythm-nation-1989/|archivedate=January 9, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' described the full length piece as a \"mini-musical\" which \"told the morality tale of two shoeshine boys who discover the Rhythm Nation.\"<ref name=greatestvideos/> ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated the plot \"juxtaposes her dance routines with grim urban imagery and a plot line about drugs versus dreams.\"<ref name=adopts>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/09/17/arts/recordings-janet-jackson-adopts-a-new-attitude-concern.html|title=RECORDINGS; Janet Jackson Adopts a New Attitude: Concern |work=The New York Times|publisher=Pareles, Jon|date=2017-09-98|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Chris Willman of ''[[The LA Times]]'' considered it \"ambitious\" and \"fun,\" saying \"The can-humans-really-do-that? choreography in the three dance numbers is on a par with, and may even top, the best of brother [[Michael Jackson|Michael]]'s hoof-happy videos.\" Willman added, \"[[Miss You Much]]\" is full of joy and giddy goofiness, and establishes shyly grinning Janet\u2014a real team player in this big production number\u2014as winsome and human after some of her earlier ice-goddess poses. \"The Knowledge\" and \"Rhythm Nation\" are angrier performances; the former is a bravura solo rooftop dance, with Jackson breaking windows and knocking over objects in rage at the dying of the light. What connects these numbers is an anti-drug story, unfortunately bolstered by the glitziness-among-the-L.A.-ruins imagery of \"''[[Blade Runner]]''.\" Director [[Dominic Sena]]'s \"slick penchant for neato futuristic grime\" was also praised, adding \"the big-bass songs and the dazzling dancing say what the hokey script can't. Her feet, her body, her grace and her lightning speed are fine arguments for sobriety indeed.\"<ref name=telemusical/>\n\n<!-- UNLESS INLINE CITATIONS ARE PRESENT FOR THE AWARDS, THEY ARE NOT TO BE REVEALED BACK\n==Awards and accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!Award\n!Nominated work\n!Result\n|-\n|[[Billboard Music Awards]]\n|Director's Award\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Billboard Music Awards]]\n|Best Female Video Artist\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Billboard Music Awards]]\n|Tanqueray Sterling Music Video Award for Artistic Achievement \t\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]\n|10 Best 80's Music Videos\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]\n|10 Most Iconic Music Video Looks of the 80s (2013)\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Grammy Awards]]\n|Best Music Video, Long Form (''Rhythm Nation 1814 Film'')\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Legends in Concert]]\n|Janet Jackson & \"Rhythm Nation\"\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[MTV]]\n|Bust Up: Best Dance Video Ever\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Awards]]\n|Best Choreography in a Video\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Awards]]\n|Best Dance Video\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Awards]]\n|[[Video Vanguard Award]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[National Museum of Women in the Arts]]\n|\"Rhythm Nation\" outfit\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]\n|\"Women Who Rock: Vision, Passion, Power\" Exhibit (\"Rhythm Nation\" outfit and lyrics, 2011)\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]\n|\"Women Who Rock: Vision, Passion, Power\" songwriting exhibit (\"Rhythm Nation\")\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]\n|Ten Best Apocalyptic Dance Music Videos (2011)\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]\n|10 Favorite Dancing Musicians (2011)\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Slant Magazine]]\n|Greatest Music Videos of All Time\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Soul Train Awards]]\n|Music Video of the Year\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[VH1]]\n|100 Greatest Videos (#37)\n|{{won}}\n|}\n -->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|OAwaNWGLM0c|Official music video on \"Vevo\"}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|janet-jackson|rhythm-nation}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Janet Jackson singles}}\n\n[[Category:Black-and-white music videos]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video]]\n[[Category:Janet Jackson]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Dominic Sena]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rhythm Nation\n| starring       = [[Janet Jackson]]\n| director       = [[Dominic Sena]]\n| producer       = \n| studio         = [[A&M Records]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1989|09|19|mf=y}} <small>(premiere)</small>\n| runtime        = {{Duration|m=4|s=27}}\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| music          = Janet Jackson, [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n}}\n\nThe '''music video''' for recording artist [[Janet Jackson]]'s single '''\"[[Rhythm Nation]]\"''' was directed by [[Dominic Sena]]. It was filmed as part of the long-form video ''Rhythm Nation 1814 Film'' at a power plant located in [[Pasadena, California]]. The video is notable for its \"post-apocalyptic\" warehouse setting, the unisex black military-style uniforms in which Jackson and her dancers were outfitted, and its choreography, considered to \"set the template for hundreds of videos to come in the Nineties and aughts.\"\n\nThe video's outfit has received various tributes, being displayed at [[Walt Disney World]] theme park, [[Rock & Roll Hall of Fame]]'s \"Women Who Rock: Vision, Passion, Power\" exhibit, and the [[National Museum of Women in the Arts]]. A wax figure of Jackson wearing the outfit was also included in [[Madame Tussaud]]'s exhibits in [[Hollywood]] and [[New York City]], as well as Tussaud's [[Rock Circus]] exhibit in [[London]]. The song and choreography is also a mainstay at [[talent shows]] worldwide, and has been performed at ''[[The X Factor]]'', ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'', and ''[[America's Best Dance Crew]]'', with an [[Australia]]n music show also named after the song. Various actors and choreographers, including [[Wade Robson]] and [[Travis Payne]], have cited Jackson and the \"Rhythm Nation\" routine as a primary influence to their careers.\n\nIt won multiple accolades, including [[MTV]]'s [[Video Vanguard Award]] for Jackson's impact on entertainment. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' considered the video \"legendary,\" and ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' included it in a list of 10 Favorite Dancing Musicians, calling Jackson \"a brilliant dancer\" whom it said had \"arguably had a greater long-term impact on the choreography of contemporary music videos\" even than her own brother [[Michael Jackson]] had had.<ref name=entweekly/> The publication also titled it \"the gold standard for [[dystopia]]n dance pop music videos,\" featuring \"some of the most memorable choreography in pop video history.\"<ref name=bestapocalyptic/> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' considered Janet's choreography to be \"even more enthralling\" than those of her contemporaries.<ref name=latimes>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-04-15/entertainment/ca-1888_1_janet-jackson/4|title=Janet Jackson Finally Learns to Say 'I'|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Hilburn, Robert|date=2015-04-90|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[black-and-white]], military-inspired \"Rhythm Nation\" video was directed by [[Dominic Sena]] in August 1989. It was the finale in the ''Rhythm Nation 1814 Film,'' following videos for \"[[Miss You Much]]\" and \"The Knowledge\", respectively. Known for its high-octane choreography in an abandoned factory, the video won an award for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]] and was nominated for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Dance Video|Best Dance Video]] at the [[MTV Video Music Awards]], where Jackson also received the [[MTV Video Vanguard Award]].<ref>{{citation|title=MTV Video Music Awards nominees|newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|date=20September 5, 1990|page=5}}</ref><ref name=\"MTVMVA\">{{citation|author=Francesca Chapman|title=Sinead Takes MTV's Top Video Award|newspaper=[[Philadelphia Daily News]]|date=20September 7, 1990|page=65}}</ref> \"Rhythm Nation\" ranked at thirty-seven on [[VH1]]'s \"Greatest 100 Videos\" and forty-four on [[MTV]]'s \"100 Greatest Videos Ever Made\". The video features a young [[Tyrin Turner]]. The success of \"Rhythm Nation\" allowed Sena to direct such subsequent films as ''[[Swordfish (film)|Swordfish]],'' ''[[Gone in 60 Seconds (2000 film)|Gone in 60 Seconds]],'' and ''[[Season of the Witch (2011 film)|Season of the Witch]].''\n\n==Development==\nThe \"Rhythm Nation\" video was filmed simultaneously with \"[[Miss You Much]]\" and \"The Knowledge,\" which were later combined to form the long-form music video ''Rhythm Nation 1814 Film.'' The video was filmed over a period of twenty days at the Pasadena Power Plant in [[Pasadena, California]], and served as the finale in the series.\n\nSpeaking to MTV, Jackson said, \"I knew who I wanted to direct \u2019Rhythm Nation,\u2019 that was simple: Dominic Sena. After working with him on \u2019[[Let's Wait Awhile]],\u2019 I absolutely fell in love with him. [...] Dominic understood story, and he could put onscreen, from front to back, the whole picture you had in your head.\" Deciphering the video's scenery, Jackson explained, \"the foggy, smoky street and the dark, black-and-white tone, that was all intentional. When you've done a lot of videos, it can be difficult to keep it fresh and new. You have to try something you've never done, in fear of looking like something you've already created.\"<ref name=video>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zrBolXPYq40C&pg=RA4-PT179|title=I Want My MTV: The Uncensored Story of the Music Video Revolution|publisher=Tannenbaum, Rob|page=179|date=October 11, 2027|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The video was shot in black-and-white to locate everybody's skin tone within shades of grey, portraying the ''Rhythm Nation'''s slogan: ''\"We are like-minded individuals, sharing a common vision, pushing toward a world rif of color-lines.\"''<ref>The Face Magazine, 1990. Page 77</ref> \"There were so many races in that video, from Black to White and all the shades of gray in between. [[Black-and-white photography]] shows all those shades, and that's why we used it,\" said Jackson.<ref name=ebony>[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]'', February 1990. Page 50</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Janet Jackson Rhythm Nation.jpg|thumb|Jackson (center) performing in the music video for \"Rhythm Nation\" surrounded by male and female dancers, all outfitted in unisex black military-style uniforms.]] -->\n\"We're living in a very visual time right now,\" Jackson explains. \"That's why videos are so important. Before, they really weren't. They play such an important part in the music business. The next is the live show. But the first they ever see of you is the video.\"<ref>[[British Vogue]], 1990. Page 578</ref> Describing Jackson on the set of the video, journalist [[David Ritz]] said \"Janet Jackson's mood seems retiring, but underneath, like so much else about her, there's more than meets the eye. For hours she obliges the camera during a grueling photography session on a sun-soaked day at the [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] Power Plant, a central locale for her black-and-white-dance video, a mysterious and metaphorical work dramatizing the concerns of ''Rhythm Nation.\"'' Jackson's clothes were considered to reflect \"a quiet sadness,\" being \"cooperative to a fault, yet inwardly shy.\"<ref name=essence>Essence Magazine, March 1990. Page 54</ref>\n\nJackson was often questioned for her black attire and uniforms, saying \"A lady came up to me and asked, 'Why do you always wear so much black? Is it because it is slimming?'\"<ref name=ebony/> \"Wearing black shows that for once that you can represent something positive and not negative,\" she emphasized, and offered harsh words for those who equate negativity with the color black, referring to the day the [[stock market]] crashed being known as \"[[Black Monday (1987)|Black Monday]]\". Jackson responds. Jackson recalled being hurt over the comments of an [[African-American]] critic who considered her black attire \"drab,\" saying \"He's been brainwashed because he can't see what I'm trying to show - and that hurt me so bad. I would hope that everyone will understand that for once black represents something good.\"<ref name=ebony/> \"That's why I decided the color scheme for ''Rhythm Nation'' - the costumes, the cover art, the overall feeling - would be positively, uncompromisingly Black.\"<ref name=essence/> Several label executives reportedly told Jackson the album and video wouldn't have \"crossover\" appeal. With Jackson's persistence, the video became \"the most far-reaching single project the company has ever attempted.\"<ref name=ebony/> In a later interview, Jackson said \"The concept basically was very industrial [[black and white]], not wanting any color brought to it\" - \"no color lines is was it was, so everyone is all somewhat of the same kind of tone.\" \"Dominic Sena directed it, it was a twenty day shoot. A lot of work, long hours.\"<ref>http://www.mtv.com/videos/misc/213453/on-the-rhythm-nation-video.jhtml On 'The 'Rhythm Nation' Video'</ref> Sena commented \"She's always out there trying to give people something different and fresh, and exciting to look at. If it's been done before she doesn't want anything to do with it, it's like 'let's start over'. Part of the reason she gravitated toward a new choreographer this time, a young guy who hadn't had that much experience, an amazing street dancer, and they developed a rapport and she said 'nobody's seen this guy's stuff before, I'll work with him. We'll develop these steps and give people something fresh to look at.\"<ref>Making of \"Rhythm Nation\", Rhythm Nation 1814 Film release</ref>\n\n==Choreography==\nThe video's choreography has been considered one of the most recognizable and imitated routines in pop culture. Co-choreographer Anthony Thomas said, \"she's not a trained dancer/ It comes from her soul. She's a natural. She's unbelievable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-03-02/entertainment/ca-1920_1_jackson-dances|title=Jackson Dances--'It Comes From Her Soul' |work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Wine, Steven|date=2002-03-90|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' included the video in a list of \"10 Favorite Dancing Musicians\", calling Jackson \"a brilliant dancer\" who has \"arguably had a greater long-term impact on the choreography of contemporary music videos\" than [[Michael Jackson]], setting a format for \"hundreds\" of subsequent videos.<ref name=rollingstone>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/rolling-stone-readers-pick-their-10-favorite-dancing-musicians-20110714/8-janet-jackson-0596086|title=Rolling Stone Readers Pick Their 10 Favorite Dancing Musicians|work=Rolling Stone|date=July 11, 2014|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The publication said \"Jackson leads what appears to be a hip paramilitary organization through some of the most memorable choreography in pop video history.\"<ref name=bestapocalyptic/> The publication also exclaimed Jackson's \"dazzling dancing\" and the \"can-humans-really-do-that? choreography\" in the video \"is on a par with, and may even top, the best of brother Michael's hoof-happy videos\", commending her \"lightning speed\".<ref name=telemusical/>\n\n''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' commented \"Ms. Jackson and her crew put on their military jackets and did the finely choreographed routine that fans everywhere wore out countless [[VHS]] tapes rewinding to memorize.\"<ref name=poll>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/468693/the-10-best-80s-music-videos-poll-results|title=The 10 Best '80s Music Videos: Poll Results|work=Billboard|publisher=Letkemann, Jessica|date=August 11, 2011|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> ''Sweat, Tears, and Jazz Hands'' author Mike Weaver commended the video's impact on choreography, declaring \"praised for its probing lyrics and video and production innovation, made her recognized and respected dancer and performer in the industry. Janet Jackson and her crew's innovative, one-of-a-kind, funk-and-groove choreography was unlike anything seen in the history of pop music. [...] By the early '90s, every show choir and every [[Hip hop music|hiphop]] dancer wanted to cut and paste parts and pieces of the Rhythm Nation production into their set.\"<ref name=weaver>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nfAyaqJ7JSsC&pg=PT171|title=Sweat, Tears, and Jazz Hands: The Official History of Show Choir from Vaudeville to Glee|publisher=Weaver, Mike|year=2011|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The book ''Gender and Qualitative Methods'' suggested the routine represents \"self-control and military discipline\" - \"they move in unison and in the same rhythm, dancing like roots, with stiff square arm movements,\" also exhibiting [[Asia]]n martial arts.<ref name=gender/> ''[[The Orlando Sentinel]]'' regarded Jackson to portray \"Swiss-watch precision\" in the routine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1990-04-28/lifestyle/9004276096_1_milli-vanilli-lip-synced-vocals|title=Pop Concert Or Mime Show?|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=2028-04-90|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> [[Slant Magazine]] said the clip \"anointed Janet the ambassador of intricately choreographed,\" being among \"the most intricately and powerfully choreographed music videos of all time.\"<ref name=greatestvideos/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/janet-jackson-damita-jo|title=Janet Jackson: Damita Jo - Music Review |work=Slant Magazine|publisher=Cinquemani, Sal|date=March 4, 2023|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' said the routine was \"made famous by its memorably routine- infested video,\" described as \"an aerobic goose step\" by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/jul/28/artsfeatures|title=Pop review: Janet Jackson |work=The Guardian|publisher=Clarke, Betty|date=July 1, 2027|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=battle/>  [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]] ranked the video as having the \"Best Dance Moves in a Music Video\" in 2013, commenting \"the dance moves \u2014 from the finger count down to the standing split \u2014 were as crisp as the uniforms.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bet.com/music/photos/2013/09/werk-best-dance-moves-in-a-music-video.html#!090513-music-dance-moves-janet-jackson-rythm-nation|title=Werk: Best Dance Moves in a Music Video - Music |work=BET|date=2009\u201313|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> [[Geico]] also noted [[The Running Man (dance)|The Running Man]] dance gained fame through the video.<ref name=\"Geico\">{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/geico/the-happiest-dance-crazes-throughout-time|title=The Happiest Dance Crazes Throughout Time|work=Buzzfeed|publisher=[[Geico]]|date=March 13, 2006|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAnother critique stated \"most of the video consists of Jackson with background dancers performing a synchronized dance routine. Judging by the serious facial expressions and vigorous body movements of Jackson and her dancers, the men and women in \u201cRhythm Nation\u201d are confident, courageous, and display unmatched conviction.\"<ref name=crossroads/> Jackson and her dancers were analyzed to \"march toward the camera in a dominating manner\" while simultaneously \"performing moves that most humans couldn\u2019t accomplish without a personal trainer and lots of free time on their hands.\"<ref name=lageose>{{cite web|url=http://lageose9.blogspot.com/2013/05/janet-jackson-rhythm-nation.html|title=Backup Dancers From Hell: Janet Jackson \u2013 \"Rhythm Nation\"|work=Blogspot|publisher=Lageose, Brian|date=May 13, 2027|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> A brief scene potentially depicting sexuality in the video's choreography was also debated, though the video was ultimately praised for its depiction of social themes, explaining \"Although there are no sexually explicit lyrics or messages in \u201cRhythm Nation\u201d that would be obvious to audiences, there is a short scene two minutes and thirty eight seconds into the music video that is somewhat sexual. [...] Instead of using sexual elements to attract audiences, it portrays the strong bond between entertainers and social activists with a common goal.\"<ref name=crossroads/>\n\n==Outfit==\nThe outfit worn for the video and performances of the song is infamous in popular culture. Jackson's appearance includes \"a fearless red-lipped pout and long black [[ponytail]],\" along with \"a black baseball hat with a metal \"1814\" applique, a black military-style shirt jacket with silver buckles and faux leather straps and collar, black belted pants and chunky, strappy boots.\"<ref name=sb>{{cite web|url=http://www.soulbounce.com/soul/2010/12/16_janet_jackson_barbie_dolls_that_wed_like_to_see.php|title=16 Janet Jackson Barbie Dolls That We'd Like To See|work=SoulBounce|date=December 10, 2009|accessdate=January 4, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203070244/http://www.soulbounce.com/soul/2010/12/16_janet_jackson_barbie_dolls_that_wed_like_to_see.php|archivedate=December 3, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Another analysis observed Jackson and her dancers \"dressed in black, cadet-style costumes that cover the entire body except the face.\"<ref name=crossroads/> A biography of Jackson stated she attempted her performances to \"center around her and her dancers, who would act as \"soldiers\" in a kind of army of reformers. Her outfit was a dark, buttonedup uniform, and she moved in tight formation with her dancers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bp5bAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT46|title=\nJanet Jackson - Cindy Dyson - Google Books|work=Infobase Learning|publisher=Dyson, Cindy|year=2000|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' also said the clip \"stars Ms. Jackson buttoned up tight in a tailored uniform, with an Army issue coat, epaulets and combat boots.\"<ref name=battle>{{cite web|url=http://www2.nytimes.com/1990/04/22/arts/tv-view-have-women-surrendered-in-mtv-s-battle-of-the-sexes.html?pagewanted=4&src=pm|title=TV VIEW; Have Women Surrendered In MTV's Battle of the Sexes? - Page 4 |work=The New York Times|publisher=Texier, Katherine|date=October 11, 2014|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> An additional anecdote from the publication noted \"Ms. Jackson, done up in black military-inspired garb, was eager to rail against societal ills like racism and domestic abuse.\"<ref name=tempest>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/04/arts/capitalizing-on-jackson-tempest.html?pagewanted=2|title=Capitalizing On Jackson Tempest - Page 2 |work=The New York Times|publisher=Ogunnaike, Lola|date=February 4, 2004|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Janet jackson.png|thumb|Jackson performing \"Rhythm Nation\" on the [[Number Ones, Up Close and Personal]] tour, 2011.]]\nChris Ryan of [[MTV]] praised Jackson's look as trendsetting, saying \"Janet took her place at the top of the trendsetting heap.\" MTV's Rebecca Thomas also commented Jackson \"made a signature of dangling-key earrings, boxy black hats and suits adorned in gold hardware\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/04/02/janet-jacksons-look-the-good-the-bad-and-the-wtf/|title=Janet Jackson\u2019s Look: The Good, The Bad And The WTF!?|publisher=MTV|date=April 10, 2002|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1706906/rihanna-777-tour-television-special.jhtml|title=Rihanna Brings '777,' '90s Flashbacks And Dancehall To Brooklyn|publisher=MTV|date=May 13, 2008|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Julianne Escobedo Shepherd of [[MTV News|MTV Style]] spoke about its influence, recalling that \"everyone wanted to dress like her\" and dance classes would \"dedicate hours\" to the video's choreography; \"she had her own personal Rhythm Nation hardware and bondage straps; I can't figure out or remember if she predated the Boy London hardware caps, but both were around the same time, and she was influential enough that it's not unlikely her steez gave them the idea.\"<ref name=style>{{cite web|url=http://style.mtv.com/2013/05/16/janet-jackson-style-icon/|title=Style Icon: Janet Jackson - MTV Style|publisher=MTV News|date=May 13, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>  An additional critique regarded the video's wardrobe \"intimidating\" and \"uniform fetish,\" likened to \"some type of dark-ops cadet corps.\"<ref name=lageose/> Other aspects of Jackson's ensemble in the clip are also regarded as influential. ''[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]'' also praised Jackson as a trendsetter, commenting \"she started her own movement with the hoop earrings with the solo key.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://photos.essence.com/galleries/essence-icon-janet-jackson?slide=24140|title=ESSENCE Icon: Janet Jackson|work=Essenceaccessdate=04-01-14}}</ref> Retail outlet [[Karmaloop]] called Jackson's snapback hat \"80s signature style\", selling a hat based on Jackson's.<ref name=karma>{{cite web|url=http://www.karmaloop.com/product/The-Rhythm-Nation-Leather-Snapback/385818|title=This Is A Love Song Hat Rhythm Nation Snapback |work=Karmaloop|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> MTV credited the hat worn in the video as one of the reasons for the snapback hat's revival in popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://style.mtv.com/2013/01/15/rihanna-ciara-leather-snapback/|title=Get A Leather Snapback Like Rihanna, Kat Graham, Ciara And Brandy|publisher=MTV|date=January 13, 2015|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' included the outfit at number nineteen on a list of 50 Stars Who Rocked Fashion, commenting Jackson adopted a \"crisp military look for the ladies \u2014 with epaulets, cadet caps, fierce tailoring.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20309550_20536569_21066616,00.html|title=\nJanet Jackson - 50 Stars Who Rocked Fashion: Top 25 |work=Entertainment Weekly|date=October 11, 2014|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Lucky (magazine)|Lucky Magazine]]'' ranked the video among \"The 18 Most Stylishly Influential Music Videos of All Time\".<ref name=lucky>{{cite web|url=http://www.luckymag.com/style/2013/11/most-stylish-music-videos_slideshow_item15_16|title=Janet Jackson, \"Rhythm Nation\" - The 18 Most Stylishly Influential Music Videos Of All Time|work=Lucky Magazine|date=2011\u201313|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The same year, ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' listed \"Rhythm Nation\" among the \"10 Most Iconic Music Video Looks of the 80s\".<ref name=cosmopolitan>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/news/all-hail-acid-wash-denim|title=10 Most Iconic Music Video Looks of The 80s |work=Cosmopolitan|publisher=Manning, Charles|date=November 13, 2006|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, Alexander Fury of ''[[The Independent]]'' called Jackson a \"style icon\", exclaiming \"the artwork created with Eighties illustrator [[Tony Viramontes]] for ''[[Control (Janet Jackson album)|Control]]'' stands the test of time, as does the video for 1989's \"Rhythm Nation\", adding he was \"obsessed\" with the video's \"get-up of quasi-military uniform accessorised with a single key on a hoop earring.\" Fury also said Jackson \"deserves a place in the fashion hall of fame\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/fashion/features/alexander-fury-ive-long-been-obsessed-with-rhythm-nation-8538095.html|title=Alexander Fury: I've long been obsessed with Rhythm Nation - Features - Fashion|work=The Independent|publisher=Fury, Alexander|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nThe themes of unity among the dancers and various ethnicities, as well as gender equality, has received praise from critics.\n\n[[Slant Magazine]] observed \"The solidarity of Janet Jackson's multi-racial Rhythm Nation dancers is evoked with hyper-synchronized movements while their individuality is expressed via their separate, distinct dances.\"<ref name=greatestvideos/> ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised Jackson as a feminist, proclaiming \"although most female characters on [[MTV]] are still reclining, swept off their feet by the fantasies of self-serving musicians and video directors, more singers are getting up and standing on their own two feet. You only have to catch Janet Jackson's hit, ''Rhythm Nation'' to be convinced that a change has taken place,\" calling it \"a far cry from the lascivious bodies in various states of undress that flood the channel.\"<ref name=battle/> ''[[34th Street Magazine]]'' applauded the video's implication of gender neutrality, saying \"\u201cRhythm Nation\u201d makes a far superior statement on the fluidity of gender. In this video, men and women dress and dance identically and no one\u2019s really sexualized. Everyone just knows how to move. In other words, sometimes the best way to send a positive message is not to try so damn hard.\"<ref name=partofme/> The clip's theme of activism and leadership was also commended, writing \"instead of using sexual elements to attract audiences, it portrays the strong bond between entertainers and social activists with a common goal,\" in an attempt to speaks \"particularly to young people and encourages them to be the leaders of tomorrow. Jackson passes on the message of social activist Mahatma Gandhi who once said, \u201cYou must be the change you wish to see in the world.\"<ref name=crossroads/> A biography stated the video spreads \"a message of love that was neither naive not superficial.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G132LEhM4ucC&pg=PA61|title=Michael Jackson, the Man Behind the Mask: An Insider's Story of the King of Pop|publisher=Jones, Bob|year=2005|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe video features dancers of \"[[African-American]], [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]], and [[Asia]]n ancestry,\" aiding Jackson in becoming known for \"breaking existing racial stereotypes specifically toward African-American women,\" depicting her as a \"socially responsible citizen with dignity and grace.\"<ref name=crossroads/> The backing dancers in the video were thought to represent \"[[Activism|social activists]]\", shrouded by \"empty surroundings\" deciphered as \"the indifferent attitudes in society.\" Jackson and her dancers were considered \"confident, courageous,\" and displaying \"unmatched conviction\". The video was used as an example of \"positive gender performance of black women in a music video\" in the book ''Gender and Qualitative Methods'', considered to produce \"a new kind of desire and a new position for a female viewer (and listener).\" The video's director was noted to construct Jackson as \"a creative, intelligent professional, someone who aims at promoting the status of black people, especially women.\"\nDressed in identical uniforms, Jackson and the dancers \"move in unison and in the same rhythm, dancing like roots, with stiff square arm movements. ... Jackson is also dressed in a uniform and is performing asexually and almost anonymously in front of, but as one of the members of the group.\"<ref name=gender>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7f7nFXfmPBMC&pg=PA92|title=Gender and Qualitative Methods|publisher=J\u00e4rviluoma, Helmi|date=October 3, 2021|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The video was also one of the only popular music videos considered suitable to be broadcast to [[US troops]] in [[Middle Eastern]] countries such as [[Saudi Arabia]] and the [[Persian Gulf]] due to religious restrictions on the portrayal of female sexuality. Commenting on the situation, VH1 executive Jackie Sharp said \"It's the perfect women's video, because they're all buttoned up to the neck and nobody touches\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,313333,00.html|title=Middle East Cover-Up |work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Harris, Mark|date=2015-02-91|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Long-form music video==\nThe full-length music video, known as the ''Rhythm Nation 1814 Film'', consists of the videos for \"[[Miss You Much]]\", \"The Knowledge\", and \"Rhythm Nation\", filmed simultaneously over a period of twenty days. It received a [[Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video]]. The video premiered in full on September 16, 1989 on MTV to high ratings, and was aired several times the following week.<ref name=telemusical>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-09-16/entertainment/ca-285_1_fancy-footwork|title=TV Reviews : Fancy Footwork Rescues Pretentious Jackson Show |work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Willman, Chris|date=2016-09-89|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Producer [[Jimmy Jam]] said \"The concept for the half-hour, long-form video was already in the works when we recorded the album. Janet's [[choreographer]] was here, so we knew what the steps were going to be for the songs, how the story would be treated, and how the video was going to look. [...] We actually tried to make the album sound a little like the black-and-white images in the video, rather than adapting the video to the album. A lot of the music was treated almost as [[soundtrack]].\"<ref>''[[Keyboard (magazine)|Keyboard]]'', May 1990. Pages 26-27</ref> While filming \"The Knowledge\", Jackson collapsed from exhaustion after filming for over 25 consecutive hours, explaining \"That's the one area where I must be careful. Sometimes I won't sleep, won't stop reviewing, won't stop searching for ways to improve the projects. The projects absorb me. When we were filming the long video, I actually collapsed.\"<ref name=ritz>Essence Magazine, March 1990. Page 116</ref> Describing the situation, journalist [[David Ritz]], who attended the video's filming, commented \"Looking at \"The Knowledge,\" it appears that Janet's physical breakdown came at the emotional climax of the video. \"[[Prejudice]], no!\" she cries, kicking and smashing windows with the anger of a soul possessed. \"[[Ignorance]], no! [[Bigotry]], no! [[Illiteracy]], no!\" she bemoans, before falling onto the ledge of the roof, dangerously positioned on the edge, ominous clouds of change racing overhead.\"<ref name=ritz/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe \"Rhythm Nation\" video received favorable reviews from critics and journalists, focusing on its theme of unity and choreography. Comparing [[Lady Gaga]] to Jackson, Kyle Anderson of [[MTV News]] described it as \"the clip that sent Jackson into the stratosphere as an envelope-pushing pop star.\"<ref name=ryan>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.mtv.com/2010/06/02/lady-gaga-alejandro-video-preview/|title=\u2018Alejandro\u2019 Video Preview: Lady Gaga Tips Her Hat To Madonna And Janet Jackson|publisher=MTV|date=June 10, 2002|accessdate=January 4, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140108233429/http://newsroom.mtv.com/2010/06/02/lady-gaga-alejandro-video-preview/|archivedate=January 8, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote =\n\"Shot in stark black and white and set in a smokey, oppressive factory setting, Jackson leads what appears to be a hip paramilitary organization through some of the most memorable choreography in pop video history. The future may look bleak, but at least it's funky.\" \u2014 [[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]<ref name=bestapocalyptic/>\n\n\"Janet's dance nation is a hard, angular, geometric battle plan, and as the title track's stunning, monochromatic video clip confirms, the schematic first calls for an almost [[Zen]]-like transcendence of self.\" \u2014 [[Slant Magazine]]<ref name=slant>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/best-singles-of-the-1980s/P4|title=The 100 Best Singles of the 1980s - Feature |work=Slant Magazine|date=August 12, 2020|accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n| width  = 30em\n| align  = right\n| quoted = 1\n}}\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called the video \"legendary,\" and ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' included it in a list of \"10 Favorite Dancing Musicians,\" calling Jackson \"a brilliant dancer\" who has \"arguably had a greater long-term impact on the choreography of contemporary music videos\" than [[Michael Jackson]]. The publication added the video \"set the template for hundreds of videos to come in the Nineties and aughts.\"<ref name=entweekly>{{cite web|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/glee-season-5-episode-7-puppet-master/2/|title='Glee' recap: No Strings Attached|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=November 13, 2029|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=rollingstone/> It was also included in a list of the \"Ten Best [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|Apocalyptic]] Dance Music Videos\" in 2011, heralded as \"the gold standard for [[dystopia]]n [[Dance-pop|dance pop]] music videos\" which features \"some of the most memorable choreography in pop video history.\"<ref name=bestapocalyptic>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/ten-best-apocalyptic-dance-music-videos-20110406/janet-jackson-rhythm-nation-1989-0545021|title=Ten Best Apocalyptic Dance Music Videos|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=04-06-11}}</ref> ''[[The Sun Sentinel]]'' called it \"dark, futuristic,\" and \"unforgettable,\" adding \"No one can witness the militaristic precision of Rhythm Nation, which gives the impression that a really angry pep squad has taken over the dance floor, and not see how Janet's style has been sampled, borrowed and stolen over and over ... and over.\"<ref name=sun>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2001-03-18/entertainment/0103160621_1_mtv-icon-janet-jackson-pop-culture|title=Welcome To Planet Janet: It's Our World|work=The Sun Sentinel|publisher=Winston, Sherri|date=March 1, 2018|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' listed it among the \"10 Most Iconic Music Video Looks of the 80s\", saying \"How do you step out from behind the shadow of the world\u2019s biggest pop star? You strap on some black, wear a key as an earring and dance like you\u2019re going to war. Janet is a style General and all the rest better fall in line.\"<ref name=cosmopolitan/> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' ranked the video among the \"100 Greatest Music Videos\", calling the \"stunning, monochromatic\" video it \"one of the most intricately and powerfully choreographed music videos of all time,\" saying \"the solidarity of Janet Jackson's multi-racial Rhythm Nation dancers is evoked with hyper-synchronized movements while their individuality is expressed via their separate, distinct dances.\"<ref name=greatestvideos>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/100-greatest-music-videos/P2|title=100 Greatest Music Videos - Feature |work=Slant Magazine|publisher=Gonzalez, Ed|date=June 3, 2029|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The publication observed Jackson \"saw dance as a movement in both senses of the word: an athletic extension of ones own socio-political force of will,\" as well as a \"obliterator of races, genders, creeds,\" calling for a \"[[Zen]]-like transcendence of self.\"<ref name=slantreview>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/janet-jackson-janet-jacksons-rhythm-nation-1814/1826|title=Janet Jackson: Janet Jackson's Rhythm Nation 1814 - Music Review |work=Slant Magazine|publisher=Henderson, Eric|date=September 9, 2006|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> The publication also stated, \"if the song's music video inadvertently recalled the spirit of [[Leni Riefenstahl]], its vision of unity through mandatory multiculturalism reverses the [[Nazi]] demagogue's ideology.\"<ref name=greatestdance>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/100-greatest-dance-songs/P8|title=100 Greatest Dance Songs - Feature |work=Slant Magazine|date=January 6, 2030|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Additional commentary said the clip \"wasn\u2019t the norm for most things in the 80s, let alone a pop music video.\"<ref name=afropunk>{{cite web|url=http://www.afropunk.com/profiles/blogs/are-you-a-part-of-the-rhythm-nation|title=Are You A Part of the Rhythm Nation|publisher=Afro-punk.com|date=March 13, 2007|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Another review considered it \"groundbreaking\" and \"famous for its dynamic choreography in an abandoned factory,\" exclaiming \"Fast-paced and bold, viewers become hooked to the catchy tunes and soulful sounds of the groundbreaking dance video.\"<ref name=crossroads>{{cite web|url=http://christophertorrenueva.wordpress.com/tag/rhythm-nation/|title=Rhythm Nation - CROSSING CROSSROADS|work=Wordpress|publisher=Torrenueva, Christopher|date=February 10, 2013|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[PopEater]]'' commented \"Known for her scene-setting, story-telling videos, her call to action video for 'Rhythm Nation' is no exception\", adding Jackson's \"military-styled high kicks and dance sequences take the cake.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popeater.com/hot-topics/janet-jackson-music-videos/|title=Janet Jackson's Iconic Music Videos|work=PopEater|publisher=Glinow, Kiki Von|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' considered it \"groundbreaking,\" also \"striking, timeless and instantly recognizable.\"<ref name=bet>{{cite web|url=http://www.bet.com/music/photos/2012/05/the-evolution-of-janet-jackson.html#!051512-music-evolution-janet-jackson-rhythm-nation-album|title=The Evolution of Janet Jackson - Music - BET|date=2005\u201312|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20396305_84846,00.html|title=Action Jacksons - Michael Jackson Remembered |work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Seymour, Craig|date=2007-12-99|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Elena Gooray of ''[[34th Street Magazine]]'' praised the video's overall theme, concept, and wardrobe, exclaiming \"Janet\u2019s messages? Justice, togetherness, the power of dance. Those ideas are simple and almost by definition inoffensive. Her use of military themes? Only to inspire her wardrobe and some incredibly synchronized dance routines with bangin\u2019 choreography.\"<ref name=partofme>{{cite web|url=http://34st.com/2012/04/part-of-me/|title=We want no part of 'Part of Me' |work=34th Street Magazine|publisher=Gooray, Elena|date=April 12, 2006|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\nMusic journalist [[Richard Croft (tenor)|Richard Croft]] considered it \"captivating, saying \"Anyone with an interest in music videos, dancing, military jackets or nunchucks \u2013 you need to see the short film that accompanied \u2018Rhythm Nation\u2019. It is incredible, one of the top five music videos ever made.\" Croft added, \"I\u2019ve never seen dancing like that in a video, and no matter how many times I see it, I can never look away. It\u2019s captivating. \u2018Rhythm Nation\u2019 is the most empowering, come-on-get-up song in the world. They should play it before sporting matches like the national anthem. Yet the lyrics never say that thinking positively and coming together is all we need to do to achieve our goals \u2013 there was work to do in 1989, there\u2019s work to do now. No struggle, no progress.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thegospelaccordingtorichardcroft.wordpress.com/2010/06/01/20-janet-jackson-rhythm-nation-1989/|title=20. Janet Jackson \u2013 \u2018Rhythm Nation\u2019 (1989)|work=Wordpress|publisher=Croft, Richard|date=June 10, 2001|accessdate=January 4, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109000519/http://thegospelaccordingtorichardcroft.wordpress.com/2010/06/01/20-janet-jackson-rhythm-nation-1989/|archivedate=January 9, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' described the full length piece as a \"mini-musical\" which \"told the morality tale of two shoeshine boys who discover the Rhythm Nation.\"<ref name=greatestvideos/> ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated the plot \"juxtaposes her dance routines with grim urban imagery and a plot line about drugs versus dreams.\"<ref name=adopts>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/09/17/arts/recordings-janet-jackson-adopts-a-new-attitude-concern.html|title=RECORDINGS; Janet Jackson Adopts a New Attitude: Concern |work=The New York Times|publisher=Pareles, Jon|date=2017-09-98|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> Chris Willman of ''[[The LA Times]]'' considered it \"ambitious\" and \"fun,\" saying \"The can-humans-really-do-that? choreography in the three dance numbers is on a par with, and may even top, the best of brother [[Michael Jackson|Michael]]'s hoof-happy videos.\" Willman added, \"[[Miss You Much]]\" is full of joy and giddy goofiness, and establishes shyly grinning Janet\u2014a real team player in this big production number\u2014as winsome and human after some of her earlier ice-goddess poses. \"The Knowledge\" and \"Rhythm Nation\" are angrier performances; the former is a bravura solo rooftop dance, with Jackson breaking windows and knocking over objects in rage at the dying of the light. What connects these numbers is an anti-drug story, unfortunately bolstered by the glitziness-among-the-L.A.-ruins imagery of \"''[[Blade Runner]]''.\" Director [[Dominic Sena]]'s \"slick penchant for neato futuristic grime\" was also praised, adding \"the big-bass songs and the dazzling dancing say what the hokey script can't. Her feet, her body, her grace and her lightning speed are fine arguments for sobriety indeed.\"<ref name=telemusical/>\n\n<!-- UNLESS INLINE CITATIONS ARE PRESENT FOR THE AWARDS, THEY ARE NOT TO BE REVEALED BACK\n==Awards and accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!Award\n!Nominated work\n!Result\n|-\n|[[Billboard Music Awards]]\n|Director's Award\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Billboard Music Awards]]\n|Best Female Video Artist\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Billboard Music Awards]]\n|Tanqueray Sterling Music Video Award for Artistic Achievement \t\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]\n|10 Best 80's Music Videos\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]\n|10 Most Iconic Music Video Looks of the 80s (2013)\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Grammy Awards]]\n|Best Music Video, Long Form (''R